# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: agriculture-commissioner
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The **50 State quarters** (authorized by Pub.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] 2534, enacted December 1, 1997) were a series of circulating commemorative quarters released by the United States Mint.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Minted from 1999 through 2008, they featured unique designs for each of the 50 US states on the reverse.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The 50 State Quarters Program was started to support a new generation of coin collectors, and it became the most successful numismatic program in US history, with roughly half of the US population collecting the coins, either in a casual manner or as a serious pursuit.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The US federal government so far has made additional profits of $3 billion from collectors taking the coins out of circulation.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] In 2009, the US Mint began issuing quarters under the 2009 District of Columbia and US Territories Program.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The Territories Quarter Program was authorized by the passage of a newer legislative act, H.R.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] This program features the District of Columbia, Puerto Rico, American Samoa, Guam, the United States Virgin Islands, and the Northern Mariana Islands.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The 50 State Quarters program was initially inspired by a 1992 Royal Canadian Mint program, "Canada 125", marking the 125th anniversary of the country's Confederation with a series of commemorative 25-cent pieces representing each of its 12 (at the time) provinces and territories.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The Canada 125 program sparked a revival of interest in coin collecting among Canadians, which led American numismatists to advocate for the United States Mint to create a similar series of coins representing U.S. states.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] In 1992, Congress passed the 1996 Atlanta Centennial Olympic Games Commemorative Coin Act.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] In addition to authorizing a series of commemorative coins marking the 1996 Summer Olympics, the law also established the Citizens Commemorative Coin Advisory Committee (CCCAC) to consider ideas for future releases.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] After Treasury Secretary Lloyd Bentsen appointed the committee in December 1993, several of its members, led by David Ganz, urged the committee to endorse a state quarters program.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Initially, Ganz found support from only Charles Atherton, from the Federal Commission on Fine Arts, and Dan Hoffman, a young numismatist from South Carolina who also served on the CCCAC.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] However, by 1995, the CCCAC finally endorsed the idea.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The committee then sought the support of Representative Michael Castle (R-Delaware), chairman of the House Banking subcommittee with jurisdiction over the nation's coinage.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Castle's initial caution was resolved when Diehl suggested the coins be issued in the order the states entered the Union or ratified the Constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Delaware, Castle's home state, was the first state to ratify the Constitution, and would thus get to be the first state to have its quarter released.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Castle subsequently held hearings and filed legislation to authorize the program.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Despite the support of the director of the mint and the Treasury Secretary-appointed CCCAC, the Treasury Department opposed the 50 States Quarters Program, as commemorative coinage had come to be identified with abuses and excesses.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The Mint's economic models estimated the program would earn the government between $2.6 billion and $5.1 billion in additional seignorage and $110 million in additional numismatic profits.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Diehl worked with Castle behind the scenes to move legislation forward despite the Treasury's opposition to the program.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] However, the Treasury suggested to Castle that the department should conduct a study to determine the feasibility of the program.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] With Diehl's advice, Castle accepted the Treasury's offer, and the agreement was codified in the United States Commemorative Coin Act of 1996.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The act also authorized the Secretary to proceed with the 50 States Quarters Program without further congressional action if the results of the feasibility study were favorable.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The Treasury Department engaged the consulting firm Coopers and Lybrand to conduct the study in 1997, which confirmed the Mint's demand, seignorage, and numismatic profit projections for the program.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Among other conclusions, the study found that 98 million Americans were likely to save one or more full sets of the quarters (at the program's conclusion, the Mint estimated that 147 million Americans collected the 50 state quarters).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Nevertheless, the Treasury Department continued to oppose the program and declined to proceed with it without a congressional mandate to do so.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] In 1997, Congress issued that mandate in the form of S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] 1228, the 50 States Commemorative Coin Program Act, which was signed into law by President Bill Clinton on December 1, 1997.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The 50 State quarters were released by the United States Mint every ten weeks, or five each year.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] They were released in the same order that the states ratified the Constitution or were admitted to the Union.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Each quarter's reverse commemorated one of the 50 states with a design emblematic of its unique history, traditions, and symbols.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Certain design elements, such as state flags, images of living persons, and head-and-shoulder images of deceased persons were prohibited.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The authorizing legislation and Mint procedures gave each state a substantial role and considerable discretion in determining the design that would represent their state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The majority of states followed a process by which the governor solicited the state's citizens to submit design concepts and appointed an advisory group to oversee the process.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Governors submitted three to five finalist design concepts to the Secretary of the Treasury for approval.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Approved designs were returned to the states for selection of a final design.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] States usually employed one of two approaches in making this selection.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] In 33 states, the governor selected the final recommended design, often based on the recommendations of advisory groups and citizens.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] In the other 17 states, citizens selected the final design through online, telephone, mail, or other public votes.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] US Mint engravers applied all final design concepts approved by the Treasury Secretary.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The media and public attention surrounding this process and the release of each state's quarter was intense and produced significant publicity for the program.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] In several cases, the process of creating and finalizing a design caused controversy in the represented state, with people and groups expressing disappointment that the design did not properly reflect their state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] There were disputes over which state could lay claim to certain design elements that appeared in other states, such as an ear of corn or the Rocky Mountains.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The Mint's conversion of each state's proposal into the final design that was used on the quarter also drew criticism for being overly simplified or poorly rendered.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Paul Jackson, whose design was chosen for the Missouri quarter and then pared down by the Mint, led a series of protests which included placing stickers with Jackson's original design on the reverses of 250,000 quarters and distributing them nationwide.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] In response to these criticisms, the Mint established the Artistic Infusion Program in 2003, hiring more professional artists and engravers to create better-looking designs for all commemorative coins.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The 50 State Quarters Program was the most popular commemorative coin program in the United States history; the United States Mint has estimated that 147 million Americans have collected state quarters and 3.5 million participated in the selection of state quarter designs.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] By the end of 2008, all of the original 50 States quarters had been minted and released.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The official total, according to the US Mint, was 34,797,600,000 coins.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Demand was stronger for quarters issued early in the program.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] This was due to weakening economic conditions in later years and the waning of the initial surge of demand when the program was launched.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Another factor was the reassertion of the Treasury Department's opposition to the program.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] When the director's term ended in 2000, the Treasury proceeded to reduce and finally terminate the most effective elements of the Mint's promotional program despite the high return on investment they earned.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] , nine stars (representing New Hampshire as the 9th state to ratify the U.S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] , 11 stars (representing New York as the 11th state to ratify the U.S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] skull in the center with mountains and the Missouri River in the background.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] While mintage totals of the various designs vary widely—Virginia quarters are almost 20 times as abundant as the Northern Marianas quarters—none of the regular circulating issues are rare enough to become a valuable investment.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] There was, however, a measure of collector interest over die errors in the Wisconsin quarter.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Some designs from the Denver mint feature corn without a smaller leaf, others feature a small leaf pointing upwards, and still others have the leaf bending down.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] A set of all three quarters sold on eBay in February 2005 for $300 and initially saw significant increases, such as $1500 for individual coins, but as of February 2020 PCGS lists the value of MS-62 specimens from $92 to $130 each.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Another die cast error ran with the first Delaware quarters.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Being the first model of state quarter made, the mint gave it a disproportionate weight causing vending machines to not accept it.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Some Delaware quarters appeared without the last *E*, now saying, "THE FIRST STAT".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] A major error occurred in 2000 when the reverse die of a Sacagawea dollar was combined with the obverse die of a state quarter on dollar-coin planchets to form what is known as a "mule".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] As of August 2019, only 19 of these specimens, produced on dollar planchets, are known to have escaped from the Mint.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] A 2005 Minnesota double die quarter, as well as a 2005 Minnesota quarter with extra trees (another die error), have both triggered numismatic interest.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] An unusual die break on some 2005 Kansas quarters created a humpback bison.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The United States produces proof coinage in circulating base metal and, since 1992, in separately sold sets with the dimes, quarters, and half-dollars in silver.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] For the silver issues, the 1999 set is the most valuable, being the first year of the series and with a relatively small mintage, although prices have significantly decreased since the 50 State Quarters Program ended.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The set in base metal, of this or any other year, is worth only a fraction as much.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The silver proof sets of later years, while having some intrinsic and collector worth, are also priced far lower.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] The public is cautioned to research prices before buying advertised state quarter year or proof sets.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] In general, the program increased interest in quarter and general coin collecting.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Large numbers of advertisements, quarter products and quarter information were available during the years the program ran.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Home Shopping Network, Franklin Mint, and Littleton Coin Company were among the most prominent in advertising space.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] Since the 50 State Quarters Program was expected to increase public demand for quarters which would be collected and taken out of circulation, the Mint used economic models to estimate the additional seigniorage the program would produce.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] These estimates established a range of $2.6 billion to $5.1 billion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] (At the end of the program, the Mint estimated the actual increase in seigniorage to be $3 billion.) The Mint also estimated the program would earn $110 million in additional numismatic profits.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/50-state-quarters] (The final, post-program estimate was $136.2 million.) The Mint used these estimates to support the proposed program, and the legislation enacting the 50 States Quarters program cited these estimates.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] The legality of abortion in the United States and the restrictions imposed on the procedure vary significantly, among the states or other jurisdictions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Some states prohibit abortion at any stage of pregnancy with few exceptions; others permit it up to a certain point in pregnancy, while some allow abortion throughout a pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] In states where abortion is legal, several classes of restrictions on the procedure may exist, such as parental consent or notification, requirements that patients be shown an ultrasound before obtaining an abortion, mandatory waiting periods, and counseling requirements.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] From 1973 to 2022, Supreme Court rulings in *Roe v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Casey* (1992) established federal protection for a pregnant woman's right to get an abortion, ensuring that states could not ban abortion prior to the point at which a fetus may be deemed viable.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] However, *Roe* and *Casey* were overturned by *Dobbs v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization* (2022), and states may since impose any regulation on abortion, provided it satisfies rational basis review and does not otherwise conflict with federal law.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Prior to the Court's decision in *Dobbs*, many states enacted trigger laws to ban abortion, should *Roe* be overturned.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Additionally, several states either have enacted or are in the process of enacting stricter abortion laws following *Dobbs*, and some have resumed enforcement of laws in effect prior to 1973.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] While such laws are no longer considered to violate the United States Constitution, they continue to face legal challenges in state courts.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Individual states have broad discretion to prohibit or regulate abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] As a result, the legal status of abortion varies considerably from state to state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] The Supreme Court removed this discretion and asserted the existence of a federal right to abortion in its 1973 *Roe v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Wade* decision; however, this ruling was overturned 49 years later by the Court's ruling in *Dobbs v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization* (2022).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] A number of states limit abortions to a maximum number of weeks into pregnancy, usually prior to when the fetus could survive if removed from the womb.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] For comparative purposes, the youngest child thought to have survived a premature birth in the United States was Curtis Means born on July 5, 2020, in Birmingham, Alabama, at a gestational age of 21 weeks and one day.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p01] Moreover, due to the Hyde Amendment, many state health programs which poor women rely on for their health care do not cover abortions; according to the ACLU, only 17 states – including California, Illinois, and New York – offer, or require, such coverage, as of 2023.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In the aftermath of the *Dobbs* ruling, state legislation and court rulings determine most aspects of abortion access in the United States.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The following sections outline the current status of abortion law in the various states and territories; references to *weeks* refer to the number of weeks since the pregnant woman's last menstrual period, or LMP, which is typically used as a measure of how long they have been pregnant.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Alabama, with exceptions to preserve the woman's life or physical health, or in the case of fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There are no exceptions for rape or incest.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Performing an abortion is a Class A felony, with up to 99 years in prison, and attempted abortion is a Class C felony, punishable by 1 to 10 years in prison, under a law enacted in May 2019.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Alabama Attorney General Steve Marshall stated that Alabama law would allow the state to prosecute those who helped organize or finance trips by Alabamians to other states, in order to receive abortions, even if abortion were legal in those states.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In July 2023, two abortion advocacy groups filed lawsuits seeking to prevent such prosecutions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Alaska at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Alaska does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In September 2024, an Alaska superior court judge struck down the requirement that only licensed physicians provide abortions, meaning that the procedure can now also be legally performed by nurse practitioners and physician assistants.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in American Samoa, and was effectively illegal there before *Roe v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion in Arizona is legal until the point of fetal viability, a right enshrined in the state constitution by voters in 2024.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A licensed physician must perform the procedure.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Minors under the age of 18 must receive parental consent.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A total abortion ban was enacted by the Arizona Territory legislature in 1864 that was invalidated by *Roe*.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A 15-week ban trigger law was enacted in Arizona in 2022.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After the *Dobbs* decision was handed down later that year, there was confusion over which of the two laws should go into effect: Then-Governor Doug Ducey backed the 15-week ban, while then-Attorney General Mark Brnovich held that the older total ban should be operative.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A December 2022 state appeals court ruling found that the 2022 law should take precedence, but on April 9, 2024, the Republican-controlled Arizona Supreme Court ruled in *Planned Parenthood Arizona v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Mayes* that the 1864 law could be enforced.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] However, on May 1, the Arizona Legislature repealed the 1864 law, leaving the 15-week ban in place.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Legal maneuvering ensured that the legislature's repeal of the 1864 law would go into effect before the Supreme Court's removal of the injunction against it.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Governor of Arizona Katie Hobbs and state Attorney General Kris Mayes are both supporters of abortion rights, elected in 2022 as part of a nationwide backlash to the *Dobbs* decision.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In July 2023, Hobbs issued an executive order stripping local prosecutors of their ability to file prosecutions over the 15-week ban, or (if it had been revived in court) the 1864 ban, and assigning that power to Mayes, who, in turn, stated that she had no intention of ever filing such prosecutions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Proposition 139 was approved on the November 2024 ballot, establishing a right to abortion in the Constitution of Arizona up until fetal viability.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] This made the debate over the blanket bans moot, and opened up legal action over existing laws that had regulated abortion before the bans had gone into effect.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] For instance, in 2026 a Maricopa County judge ruled that the language of the amendment voided bans on telemedicine prescription of abortion medication, and requirements that patients have multiple consultations with a doctor before undergoing an abortion procedure.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Arkansas, with an exception for abortions necessary to save the life of the pregnant woman; there are no exceptions for rape, incest, or fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Doctors determined to have performed an abortion face up to 10 years in prison, and fines up to $100,000.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in California up to the point of fetal viability, or after that if necessary to preserve the life or health (including mental health) of the pregnant woman.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Nurse-midwives and other non-physician qualified medical personnel with proper training may perform abortion procedures early in pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] California does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2022, California voters approved Proposition 1, enshrining women's reproductive rights, including the right to legal abortion and contraception, in the state constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Colorado at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Minors' parents or legal guardians must receive notice before the procedure.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2008, Kristine and Michael Burton of Colorado for Equal Rights proposed Colorado Amendment 48, an initiative to amend the definition of a person to "any human being from the moment of fertilization".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On November 4, 2008, the initiative was turned down by 73.2 percent of the voters.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] 2024 Colorado Amendment 79 appeared on the ballot in November 2024.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The amendment was approved by voters, explicitly conferring the right to abortion in the Colorado state constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Connecticut up to the point of fetal viability, or after that if necessary to preserve the life or health (including mental health) of the pregnant woman.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Connecticut does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The 1821 abortion law of Connecticut was the first known law enacted in the United States to restrict abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Although this law did not completely outlaw abortions, it imposed heavier restrictions, as it prevented people from attempting or receiving abortions, which was generally through the consumption of poison, during the first four months of a pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in the District of Columbia at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The District of Columbia does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A previous statute making abortion a criminal offense in the District was repealed in 2004.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The consequence of this repeal is that abortion is completely unregulated in the District throughout the period of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Delaware up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Parental notification is required for minors under the age of 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] 55% of adults said in a poll by the Pew Research Center that abortion should be legal in all or most cases.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There was a therapeutic exceptions in the state's legislative ban on abortions by 1900.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Informed consent laws were on the books by 2007.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of May 14, 2019, the state prohibited abortions after the fetus was viable, generally some point between week 24 and 26.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] This period uses a standard defined by the United States Supreme Court in 1973 with the *Roe v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal after 6 weeks in Florida, with exceptions for rape, incest, and human trafficking (up to 15 weeks), fetal abnormalities (before the third trimester), and, throughout pregnancy, if the pregnant woman's life is in danger.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Parental consent is required for minors under the age of 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Until 2022, abortion in Florida was legal up to the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] 56% of adults said in a poll by the Pew Research Center that abortion should be legal in all or most cases.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] An abortion ban with therapeutic exception was in place by 1900.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Such laws were in place after the American Medical Association sought to criminalize abortion in 1857.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] By 2007, the state had a customary informed consent provision for abortions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] By 2013, state Targeted Regulation of Abortion Providers (TRAP) law applied to medication induced abortions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There is a privacy clause in the Constitution of Florida, and the Supreme Court of Florida had in 1989 ruled that it protected a right to abortion in the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Florida Legislature outlawed abortion after 15 weeks in 2022, and the court declined to stay that law as challenges to it made their way through the Florida legal system.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2023, the Florida Legislature enacted a "heartbeat bill" banning abortion at 6 weeks, but the law had a trigger provision, preventing it from going into effect unless the Florida Supreme Court first ruled in favor of the 15-week ban.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Court did so on April 1, 2024, and the 6-week ban took effect on May 1, 2024.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On April 1, 2024, the Court approved Amendment 4, an initiative that appeared on the 2024 ballot that, if ratified, would have allowed abortion up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The amendment failed to reach the 60% threshold needed to pass, garnering 57% of the vote.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Georgia after 5 or 6 weeks from LMP (on average, 1 to 2 weeks after a missed period), not counting a 24-hour waiting period.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Parental notification is required for minors under the age of 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Georgia Legislature enacted an abortion law in 2019 that prohibits abortions after a fetal heartbeat is detected, usually six weeks following the last menstrual period.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Enforcement of the law was blocked by a federal judge in that year, but it was reinstated after the *Dobbs* ruling.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On September 30, 2024, Fulton County Superior Judge Robert McBurney issued a ruling finding that the state constitution protects a right to privacy, and that access to abortion before fetal viability is part of that right.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The ruling struck down the law, though a spokesperson for the Attorney General of Georgia said the state would appeal; one week later, the 6-week abortion ban was provisionally restored by the Georgia Supreme Court, pending the resolution of the appeal.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion services are currently unavailable in Guam because there are no local clinicians who provide them.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] However, there have been no physicians based in Guam who have provided abortions since the last provider retired in 2016.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A 1990 law that would ban nearly all abortions is blocked by federal courts.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Attorney General of Guam Douglas Moylan is currently appealing this injunction.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Legislature of Guam passed a six-week ban in 2022 that was vetoed by Governor Lou Leon Guerrero.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Hawaii up to the point of fetal viability, or after that if necessary to preserve the life or health of the pregnant woman.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Hawaii does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of 2017, there are 28 clinics in Hawaii that will perform abortions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After viability, an abortion is only allowed if the patient's life or health is in danger.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2025, Hawaii legislators proposed a constitutional amendment to enshrine abortion and contraception rights within Hawaii's state constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Idaho, with exceptions for rape, incest, and to save the pregnant woman's life; there are no exceptions for fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Illinois up to the point of fetal viability, or after that if necessary to preserve the life or health (including mental health) of the pregnant woman.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Illinois does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2013, the Illinois Supreme Court recognized a right to abortion in the Illinois state constitution under the due process clause.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of 2017, Illinois had 40 facilities that can perform abortions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2019, the Illinois General Assembly enacted the Reproductive Health Act, which repealed all earlier state restrictions on abortion before viability, and codified reproductive rights into state law.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is currently illegal in Indiana, with exceptions for fatal fetal abnormalities, to preserve the life and physical health of the pregnant woman, or (before 10 weeks post-fertilization) in cases of rape or incest.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion in Iowa is illegal after 6 weeks of gestation, with exceptions for rape, incest, fetal abnormalities, and the pregnant woman's life.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Iowa implemented its 6-week abortion ban in July 2024.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The exact point of pregnancy at which abortion services will no longer be legal can be different from person to person.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The legal limit for getting an abortion can vary from person to person, as the development of the embryo can progress at different rates.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A health-care provider can determine how developed the embryo is.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] If one is more than 6 weeks pregnant, travel out of Iowa for an abortion may be necessary unless a requirement for exception is satisfied.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Kansas up to 22 weeks after the last menstrual period (20 weeks post-fertilization).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Kansas lawmakers approved sweeping anti-abortion legislation (HB 2253) on April 6, 2013, that says life begins at fertilization, forbids abortion based on "gender", and bans Planned Parenthood from providing sex education in schools.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2015, Kansas became the first state to ban the dilation and evacuation procedure, a common second-trimester abortion procedure.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] But the new law was later struck down by the Kansas Court of Appeals in January 2016, without ever having gone into effect.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In April 2019, the Kansas Supreme Court affirmed the lower court's decision, and ruled that the right to abortion is inherent within the state's constitution and bill of rights, such that, even if *Roe v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Wade* were overturned, and the federal protection of abortion rights is withdrawn, the right would still be allowed within Kansas, barring a change in the state constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A proposed constitutional amendment that would have superseded this ruling was decisively rejected by voters on August 2, 2022, six weeks after Roe was overturned in *Dobbs v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Kentucky, except when necessary to prevent the patient from dying, or to prevent the permanent impairment of a "life-sustaining organ".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There are no exceptions for rape, incest, or fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Performing an illegal abortion is a Class C felony, with imprisonment of 5 to 10 years, and fines of $1,000 to $10,000.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The ACLU announced plans to sue the state in court, claiming that the state constitution implicitly recognizes abortion as a legal right.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On June 30, 2022, Jefferson County Circuit Judge Mitch Perry issued a temporary restraining order blocking enforcement of the state's abortion ban, pending further hearings to determine if the ban violates the Kentucky Constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] This order temporarily allows both elective abortion providers, which are both located in Louisville, to temporarily resume elective abortions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Both the Kentucky Court of Appeals and the Kentucky Supreme Court refused a request to dissolve the restraining order; however, the trigger law banning abortions was reinstated on August 1, 2022.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2022, Kentucky voters rejected an amendment that would have denied any right to abortion in the state constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On February 16, 2023, the Kentucky Supreme Court ruled that abortion providers lacked standing to challenge the state's abortion ban, but did not elaborate on whether or not the Kentucky Constitution secured abortion rights.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Louisiana, except in cases of fetal abnormalities or when performed to save the woman's life.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A lawsuit by Hope Medical Group for Women and Medical Students for Choice challenging the ban was denied on appeal by the Louisiana Supreme Court in August 2022.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Maine up to fetal viability.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] It must be approved as necessary by a licensed physician if it's after fetal viability.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Maine does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Physicians, physician's assistants, nurse practitioners, and other professional medical providers may perform the procedure.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Maryland at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A referendum to codify abortion rights within Maryland's constitution was approved in November 2024.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Massachusetts up to 24 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After 24 weeks, abortions may only be performed if a licensed physician determines it to be medically necessary.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Parental consent is required for minors under the age of 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In December 2020, the Massachusetts state legislature enshrined abortion rights into state law.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Michigan, although a physician's approval is needed after fetal viability.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Minnesota at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In January 2023, the Minnesota Legislature enacted a bill enshrining women's reproductive rights, including the right to legal abortion and contraception, into Minnesota statutes.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Minnesota Supreme Court had previously ruled in 1995 that the Minnesota state constitution conferred a right to abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Minnesota also does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Mississippi, with exceptions when the pregnant woman's life is in danger, as well as in rape cases.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There are no exceptions for fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Attempted or completed abortion is punishable with a maximum of 10 years imprisonment.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion in Missouri is legal up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of May 2025, however, clinics in the state are not providing abortion services as a legal battle over applicable regulations continues.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] From 2022 to 2024, Missouri had a near-total abortion ban, with no exceptions provided for rape, incest, or fatal fetal abnormalities.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Amendment 3 was approved by Missouri voters in November 2024, legalizing abortion in the state up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A lawsuit filed in August 2024 by two Republican state legislators and an anti-abortion activist unsuccessfully challenged the initiative.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] However, a legal battle continued over clinic regulations that had been part of Missouri law and had significantly restricted access to abortion even before the *Dobbs* decision.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After Amendment 3 went into effect, a state judge struck down many of those regulations, ruling that they now violated the Constitution of Missouri, and several clinics began providing abortion services in the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Montana up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A 2024 Montana Supreme Court decision established that minors do not need parental consent to have an abortion, overturning a state statute.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Montana Supreme Court ruled in 1999 that abortion was a right implicitly granted by the state constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Legislative initiatives were enacted in hopes of challenging that ruling.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Montana Legislature enacted a 20-week ban in 2021, and in 2023 enacted a ban on dilation and evacuation, the most common technique used in abortions after 15 weeks.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Both laws were blocked by the courts pending a final ruling, and finally invalidated by the ratification of 2024 Montana Initiative 128.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2022, Montana voters rejected a measure that would have given embryos and fetuses legal personhood status.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2024, Montana voters ratified 2024 Montana Initiative 128, which made abortion an explicit constitutional right.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Nebraska after 12 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] 2024 Nebraska Initiative 434 was ratified by voters while 2024 Nebraska Initiative 439 was rejected, leaving the 12-week abortion ban in place.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Nevada up to 24 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Nevada does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Nevada is the only state in the country that criminalizes a woman performing a self-managed abortion by "any drug, medicine, or substance, or any instrument or other means" after the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On July 1, 2024, the State of Nevada formally certified an initiative amendment that would enshrine abortion access up until the point of fetal viability into the state constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Nevada Right to Abortion Initiative was approved in 2024, and will appear again on the November 2026 ballot.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in New Hampshire up to 24 weeks of pregnancy, although state law does not expressly confer abortion rights.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in New Jersey at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] New Jersey does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in New Mexico at all stages of pregnancy, though state law does not explicitly protect abortion access.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] New Mexico does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in New York up to 24 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] New York does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There are approximately 252 clinics in New York that perform abortions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2019, New York codified abortions rights and reproductive freedoms in state law.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] New York state Senator Alessandra Biaggi proposed a bill during the 2021–2022 session to permit taxpayers in New York to voluntarily contribute to the abortion access fund on their tax forms.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] This essentially helps create more access to abortion in the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] 2024 New York Proposition 1 was ratified by voters in November 2024.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The amendment ensures that no one in New York state can be denied rights based on "ethnicity, national origin, age, and disability", or "sex, including sexual orientation, gender identity, gender expression, pregnancy, pregnancy outcomes, and reproductive health care and autonomy".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] This expands the already existing Equal Protection Clause in the Constitution of New York which prohibits the denial of rights for a person based on "race, color, creed, or religion".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in North Carolina after the 12th week of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In the case of rape or incest, abortion is legal through the 20th week of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In the case of a "life-limiting" fetal abnormality, abortion is legal through the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] If the pregnant woman's life is determined by a qualified physician to be at risk from the pregnancy, then abortion can be legally performed at any stage of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Parental consent is required for minors under the age of 18, though a minor may obtain a judicial bypass that overrides this consent requirement.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion in North Dakota is generally illegal.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The law technically made exceptions to save the life of the pregnant woman, or, until 6 weeks into a pregnancy, in cases of rape or incest.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion was illegal in North Dakota from 2023 to 2024, until Judge Bruce Romanick ruled that the state's abortion ban violated the Constitution of North Dakota's equality provisions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2025, the ban was reinstated, after the North Dakota Supreme Court reversed the temporary holding order.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After the Supreme Court overturned *Roe v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Wade* on June 24, 2022, North Dakota moved to ban "almost all abortions, except in the case of rape, incest, or where the mother's life is at risk".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The ban was temporarily blocked by a court, and permanently enjoined by Judge Romanick in 2024.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Performing an abortion under the proposed ban was a Class C felony, punishable by up to five years in prison and up to a $10,000 fine.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In January 2025, the North Dakota Supreme Court denied the state government's request to reinstate the total ban.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2025, three of the five judges found the law "unconstitutionally vague", but state constitution requires that at least four judges must agree to strike down the law.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Before the *Dobbs* decision, the only abortion clinic operating in North Dakota was the Red River Women's Clinic, located in Fargo, which is immediately on the border with Minnesota.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In light of the legal uncertainty after the decision, the clinic moved to Moorhead, Minnesota, just on the other side of the state line.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Even when abortion was decriminalized in North Dakota, there were no abortion providers operational within the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in the Northern Mariana Islands, and was illegal there before *Roe* was overturned.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Ohio up to fetal viability.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After viability, abortion is only legal if, in the professional judgement of an attending physician, the abortion is necessary to protect the pregnant woman's life or health.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On November 7, 2023, a majority of Ohio voters voted in favor of Issue 1, which ratified an amendment to the state constitution to establish a constitutional right to abortion up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The constitutional amendment took effect on December 7, 2023.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of 2024, the interaction between the new amendment and previously existing abortion restrictions has not been tested in court.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Legislative proposals to nullify the amendment by taking the power to enforce it out of the hands of state judges were rejected by state House Speaker Jason Stephens.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Oklahoma, unless necessary to save the life of the pregnant woman.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2016, Oklahoma state legislators passed a bill to criminalize abortion for providers, potentially charging them with up to three years in prison.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On May 20, 2016, Governor Mary Fallin vetoed the bill before it could become law, citing its wording as too vague to withstand a legal challenge.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Governor Kevin Stitt signed three bills in 2021 that introduced new restrictions on abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] One bill would revoke a medical license for people who perform abortions, another would ban abortions if a heartbeat is detected, and the third would require board-certified OB-GYN doctors be the only ones who can perform abortions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of 2022, abortion is currently illegal in most cases in Oklahoma.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Oklahoma's abortion ban took effect on May 25, 2022, when Governor Kevin Stitt signed HB 4327 into law, and abortion providers have ceased offering services in Oklahoma as of that date.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] HB 4327 is modeled after the Texas Heartbeat Act, and is enforced solely through civil lawsuits brought by private citizens, making it exceedingly difficult for abortion providers to challenge the constitutionality of the statute in court.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On April 12, 2022, Governor Kevin Stitt signed into law SB 612, a bill that banned abortion indefinitely, unless the life of the pregnant woman was at stake, with no exceptions to rape and incest.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The penalty for performing an abortion is two to five years imprisonment.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Oregon at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2017, there were 20 facilities providing abortions in Oregon.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] As of January 2021, there are no major restrictions on abortion in the state, including no requirements for waiting period or parental consent for minors seeking abortions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Pennsylvania up to 24 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2024, the Pennsylvania Supreme Court ruled that the state's Medicaid program was required to pay for abortion services for participating residents.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 1980, the Supreme Court of Puerto Rico ruled that abortion rights were protected by a clause in the commonwealth's constitution that guaranteed the right to intimacy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Puerto Rico does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Rhode Island up to the point of fetal viability.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] 71% of residents reported support of passing laws to protect access to safe and legal abortion in 2018.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] There are some restrictions in Rhode Island, such as parental consent and clinic regulations in order to perform the procedure.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in South Carolina after detection of a "fetal heartbeat", up to 5 or 6 weeks from LMP (on average, 1 to 2 weeks after a missed period), not counting a 24-hour waiting period.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Parental consent is required for minors under the age of 17.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A 5-to-6-week abortion ban that had been passed before *Dobbs* as a trigger law was struck down in January 2023 by the South Carolina Supreme Court, which said it violated the state constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A newly passed 5-to-6-week ban went in effect in August 2023, after the justice who wrote the opinion in the original case retired; the new law was judged constitutional by the state supreme court.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in South Dakota, with exceptions to "preserve the life of the pregnant female", given "appropriate and reasonable medical judgement".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The ban was enacted as a trigger law in 2005.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Under the law, anyone who induces an abortion is "guilty of a Class 6 felony", with a maximum of two years imprisonment and $4,000 in fines.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2024, South Dakotans voted on Amendment G, which, if passed, would have amended the state constitution to create a right to abortion in the first two trimesters of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Tennessee, with exceptions to terminate molar or ectopic pregnancies, to remove a miscarriage, to save the life of a woman who is pregnant, or to "prevent serious risk of substantial and irreversible impairment of a major bodily function of the pregnant woman".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Doctors are permitted to use their "reasonable medical judgement, based upon the facts known to the physician at the time", to determine if a situation falls into one of these exceptions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Anyone convicted of breaking the law could face 3 to 15 years in prison, as well as up to $10,000 in fines.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in Texas, except when necessary to save the pregnant woman's life.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Wade* case, tried in Texas, stands at the center of years of national debate about the issue of abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Henry Wade was serving as District Attorney of Dallas County at the time.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On August 29, 2014, US District Judge Lee Yeakel struck down as unconstitutional two provisions of Texas' omnibus anti-abortion bill, House Bill 2 that was to come into effect on September 1.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The regulation would have closed about a dozen abortion clinics, leaving only eight places in Texas to get a legal abortion, all located in major cities.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Judge Lee Yeakel ruled that the state's regulation was unconstitutional, and would have placed an undue burden on women, particularly on poor and rural women living in west Texas and the Rio Grande Valley.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The legal challenge to the law eventually reached the Supreme Court in *Whole Woman's Health v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Hellerstedt* (2016) which ruled that the law was unconstitutional, its burden of requiring abortion doctors to have admission privileges at a local hospital within 30 miles of the center to interfere with a woman's right to an abortion from *Roe v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In May 2021, Texas lawmakers passed the Texas Heartbeat Act, banning abortions as soon as cardiac activity can be detected, typically as early as six weeks into pregnancy, and often before women know they are pregnant.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In order to avoid traditional constitutional challenges based on *Roe v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The lawsuit may be filed by people either with or without any vested interest.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The law contains an exception for abortions performed to save the mother's life.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The law was challenged in courts, though had yet to have a full formal hearing as its September 1, 2021, enactment date came due.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Plaintiffs sought an order from the U.S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Supreme Court to stop the law from coming into effect, but the Court issued a denial of the order late on September 1, 2021, allowing the law to remain in effect.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] While unsigned, Chief Justice John Roberts and Justice Stephen Breyer wrote dissenting opinions joined by Justices Elena Kagan and Sonia Sotomayor that they would have granted an injunction on the law until a proper judicial review.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Garland further noted that the United States government has "an obligation to ensure that no state can deprive individuals of their constitutional rights".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Complaint avers that Texas enacted the law "in open defiance of the Constitution".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] District Court in Austin, Texas, includes a declaration that the Texas Act is unconstitutional, and an injunction against state actors, as well as any and all private individuals who may bring a SB 8 action.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The suit was met with controversy, with critics citing concerns over the suit's politicized nature and the possible infringements on civilian rights.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Wade* on June 24, 2022, Texas completely banned abortions, except when the pregnant woman's life is at risk.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Completed or attempted providing of abortion "will be charged with a first- or second-degree felony, and will be subject to a civil penalty of at least $100,000" for each abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A first-degree felony in Texas is punishable by 5 to 99 years in prison, while a second-degree felony is punishable by 2 to 20 years in prison, with "fines of up to $10,000" being possible.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On March 7, 2023, five women who suffered serious pregnancy complications, and were denied abortions, sued the state of Texas over their near-total abortion ban, stating that the ban directly put their lives and health in danger.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The purpose of the lawsuit is to force the state to issue regulations clarifying the medical exception clause, rather than to overturn Texas's abortion ban entirely.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2023, a number of local governments in Texas near the border of New Mexico passed ordinances that make it illegal to transport or to help transport someone through those jurisdictions for the purposes of seeking an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The laws' enforcement mechanism is based on civil lawsuits, like the Texas Heartbeat Act, making them difficult to challenge in court.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Virgin Islands up to 24 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Residents of the British Virgin Islands often travel to the U.S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is *de facto* legal in Utah up to 18 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A near-total trigger ban was passed by the state legislature in 2020; however, this law is being challenged in court by Planned Parenthood of Utah on the grounds that it violates the state constitution, which establishes a right to gender equality and a right to determine family composition.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The law was enjoined from going into effect by a state trial court while the challenge to it was being heard, and the Utah Supreme Court upheld that injunction in 2024.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The currently enjoined abortion ban includes exceptions if the pregnant woman's life is at risk, as well as in cases of lethal fetal abnormalities, severe brain abnormalities, rape, or incest.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] It is a second-degree felony to perform illegal abortions under the law, punishable by 1 to 15 years in prison, and a maximum possible fine of $10,000.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Vermont at all stages of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Vermont does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In November 2022, Vermont residents voted to amend the state's constitution, now explicitly conferring abortion rights.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in Virginia up to 25 weeks of pregnancy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2020, Virginia governor, Ralph Northam signed laws that removed many of the restrictions on abortion that had been in place for decades.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Virginia became the first state to codify new protections for abortion rights in 2020.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2025, Virginia legislators advanced a state referendum that would enshrine reproductive rights within the state's constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is legal in the state of Washington.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Washington does not require a minor to notify a parent or guardian in order to obtain an abortion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2025, Washington legislators advanced a state referendum that would enshrine abortion rights within the state's constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion is illegal in West Virginia, except if necessary to preserve the life or health of a pregnant woman, if the fetus has a fatal anomaly, or if (up to 14 weeks) the pregnancy is the result of rape or incest.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The near-total ban on abortions is currently being challenged in court.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] An initial July 2023 ruling by a Dane County trial judge found that an 1849 law previously considered a trigger ban does not apply to consensual abortions performed by medical staff.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion providers in Milwaukee and Dane Counties offer abortions up to 22 weeks.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Providers in Wisconsin stopped offering abortion services in the aftermath of *Dobbs* due to the 1849 law.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] However, Wisconsin Attorney General Josh Kaul, a supporter of abortion rights, sued in state court to attempt to overturn the law; the Dane County ruling was the first in that case.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortions are offered by Planned Parenthood of Wisconsin in Milwaukee, Dane, and Sheboygan Counties, whose district attorneys have stated that they will not file charges based on the 1849 ban.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The organization initially did not resume abortions at its clinic in Sheboygan County, whose district attorney has stated that he believes the law still applies; however, they announced that abortion services would resume on December 28, 2023.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The case was expected to be ultimately decided by the Wisconsin Supreme Court; Janet Protasiewicz, an abortion rights supporter, was elected in 2023, in a contest in which abortion was a major subject of debate.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On July 2, 2025, the Wisconsin Supreme Court struck down the 1849 law.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2013, Act 37 was passed into law, necessitating admitting privileges for all abortion providers within the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Admitting privileges allow physicians the right to directly admit a patient to a nearby hospital.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Not only are these privileges difficult for abortion physicians to obtain, given the controversial nature of abortion, the Wisconsin law required admitting privileges to be obtained within one day of the law's passage.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] After Governor Walker signed the bill into law, a federal district court judge in the Western District of Wisconsin immediately granted a preliminary injunction, preventing its implementation.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A trial was held, and the court imposed a permanent injunction against the law, with the Judge noting that clinic closure was clearly the purpose of the law, as there was only one day granted for physicians to obtain compliance.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Further, the ruling found that abortion complications "are rare, and are rarely dangerous"; thus, it seems to undermine the argument that this law is needed for women's health and safety.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The case was appealed by the state's attorney; yet, the US Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit upheld the earlier ruling, and the permanent injunction.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The appeals court declared, as did the trial court judge, that the state had failed to demonstrate any obvious need for this legislation.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The state further appealed to the Supreme Court; however, this appeal was rejected, maintaining the permanent injunction of the law.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The rejection by the Supreme Court to hear the case came rather quickly after the ruling in the state of Texas' case also involving admitting privileges.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The Supreme Court's ruling in *Whole Women's Health v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Hellerstedt* found that the admitting privileges requirement created an undue burden for women, and thus interfered with the rights established in *Roe v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Abortion in Wyoming is legal until fetal viability.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] A 6-week ban was signed into law in 2026, however the law was challenged and a court temporarily blocked it from taking effect while the lawsuit proceeds.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] In 2022, state legislation attempted to make abortion illegal, except in cases of rape, incest, or harm to the health of the pregnant woman, but enforcement was blocked by the courts, pending a final decision on the law's constitutionality.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] The ban was struck down by a Wyoming judge in November 2024, a ruling upheld by the Wyoming Supreme Court in January 2026.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] On March 9, 2026, Governor Mark Gordon signed a heartbeat law passed by the Wyoming Legislature.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Opponents vowed to challenge the law in state court based on the January 2026 decision.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p02] Gordon said that while he supported the law, it was a "fragile legal effort with significant risk of ending in the courts rather than in lasting, durable policy" and suggested that the issue should ultimately be decided by state voters.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p03] Abortion is not legal at any gestational age in states displayed with a pink background.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p03] Additional limitations are given regardless, as the legality of abortion may change.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p03] Following the *Dobbs* decision which overturned *Roe v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p03] Wade*, 16 states have so far held ballot initiatives to either protect/reduce abortion rights in the state or to add/reduce protections for abortion rights in the state constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p03] In the 16 states that have so far held referendums on the abortion issue, 13 have seen the abortion rights side win, and three have seen the abortion rights side lose.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/abortion-in-the-united-states-by-state-p03] One of the three times when the abortion rights side lost, i. e. in Florida, required a 60% vote in favor, rather than 50%, in order to pass, and only got 57%.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] In the United States, each state and territory sets the age of consent either by statute or the common law applies, and there are several federal statutes related to protecting minors from sexual predators.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Depending on the jurisdiction, the legal age of consent (that is, the age at which one can consent to anyone older) is between 16 and 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states also include close-in-age exemptions, which legalize sexual activity involving those under the age of consent, when both partners are close-in-age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] In some places, civil and criminal laws within the same state conflict with each other.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] While the unrestricted age of consent is between 16 and 18 in all U.S. states, the laws have widely varied across the country in the past.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1880, the ages of consent were set at 10 or 12 in most states, with the exception of Delaware where it was seven.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] The ages of consent were raised across the U.S. during the late 19th century and the early 20th century.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1920, 26 states had an age of consent at 16, 21 states had an age of consent at 18, and one state (Georgia) had an age of consent at 14.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Small adjustments to these laws occurred after 1920.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] The last two states to raise their age of general consent from under 16 to 16 or higher were Georgia, which raised the age of consent from 14 to 16 in 1995, and Hawaii, which changed it from 14 to 16 in 2001.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Age-of-consent laws historically only applied when a female was younger than her male partner.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] By 2015, ages of consent were gender independent.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Until the late 20th century many states had provisions requiring that the teenage girl must be of "chaste character" in order for the sexual conduct to be considered criminal.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1998, Mississippi became the last state to remove the chastity provision from its code.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] The laws were designed to prosecute persons much older than their victims rather than teenagers close in age; therefore prosecutors rarely pursued teenagers in relationships with other teenagers even though some laws made close-in-age teenage relationships illegal.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] After the 1995 Landry and Forrest study concluded that men aged 20 and older produced half of the teenage pregnancies of girls between 15 and 17, states began to more stringently enforce age-of-consent laws to combat teenage pregnancy in addition to preventing adults from taking advantage of minors.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] A backlash among the public occurred when some teenagers engaging in close-in-age relationships received punishments perceived by the public to be disproportionate, and thus age-gap provisions were added to reduce or eliminate penalties if the two parties are close in age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Kercher of the Criminal Justice Center of Sam Houston State University wrote that these laws are often referred to as "Romeo and Juliet laws", though they defined Romeo and Juliet as only referring to an affirmative defense against prosecution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Previously some of these statutes only applied to heterosexual sex, leaving homosexual sex in the same age range open to prosecution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] On June 26, 2003, both heterosexual and homosexual sodomy became legal (between non-commercial, consenting adults in private) in all U.S. states, District of Columbia, and territories, under the U.S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Limon* (2005), the Kansas Supreme Court used *Lawrence* as a precedent to overturn the state's "Romeo and Juliet" law, which prescribed lesser penalties for heterosexual than homosexual acts of similar age of consent-related offenses.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Since 2005, states have been enacting Jessica's Law statutes, which provide for lengthy penalties (often a mandatory minimum sentence of 25 years in prison and lifetime electronic monitoring) for the most aggravated forms of child sexual abuse (usually of a child under age 12).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] 2422(b)} forbids the use of the United States Postal Service or other interstate or foreign means of communication, such as telephone calls or use of the internet, *to persuade or entice a minor* (defined as under 18 throughout the chapter) *to be involved in a criminal sexual act*.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] The act has to be illegal under state or federal law to be charged with a crime under 2422(b), and can even be applied to situations where both parties reside within the same state but use an instant messenger program whose servers are located in another state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] 2423(a)} forbids *transporting a minor* (defined as under 18) in interstate or foreign commerce *with the intent of engaging in criminal sexual acts* in which a person can be charged.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] This subsection is ambiguous on its face and seems to apply only when the minor is transported across state or international lines to a place where the conduct is already illegal to begin with.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States Department of Justice seems to agree with this interpretation.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] 2423(b)} forbids *traveling in interstate or foreign commerce to engage in "illicit sexual conduct"* with a minor; this is considered one form of sexual tourism.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] 2423(f) refers to Chapter 109A as its bright line for defining "illicit sexual conduct" as far as non-commercial sexual activity is concerned.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] For the purposes of age of consent, the only provision applicable is {Chapter 109A, 18 U.S.C.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] 2243(a) refers to situations where such younger person is under the age of 16 years, has attained 12 years of age, and the older person is more than four years older than the 12-to-15-year-old (children under 12 are handled under 18 U.S.C.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] So, the age is 12 years if one is within four years of the 12-to-15-year-old's age, 16 under all other circumstances.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] This law is also extraterritorial in nature to U.S. citizens and residents who travel outside of the United States.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] The Assimilative Crimes Act (18 U.S.C. § 13) incorporates local state criminal law when on federal reservations such as Bureau of Land Management property, military posts and shipyards, national parks, national forests, *inter alia*.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Consequently, if an act is not punishable under any federal law (such as 18 U.S.C.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] 2243(a) mentioned above) then the local state's age-of-consent laws would apply to the crime.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] The Protect Act § 503 of 1992 (codified at 18 U.S.C. § 2251 to 18 U.S.C. § 2260) makes it a federal crime to possess or create sexually explicit images of any person under 18 years of age regardless of consent.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Sessions*, the Supreme Court held that in the context of statutory rape offenses that criminalize sexual intercourse based solely on the ages of the participants, the generic *federal definition* of "sexual abuse of a minor" requires the age of the victim to be less than 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Article 120b of the Uniform Code of Military Justice (10 U.S.C. § 920b), to which essentially only members of the United States Armed Services and enemy prisoners of war are subject, defines the age of consent as 16 years but allows an exemption for people who are married to minors 12–15 years old.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] There is also a mistake-in-age defense if the minor is over 12, but not if the minor is under 12.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Within the United States, service members are subject to both the UCMJ and the applicable state law when "off-post".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] Depending upon the relevant status of forces agreement, United States service members are also subject to the local criminal laws of the host nation for acts committed off-post.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] (formally called the District of Columbia) is 16 with a close-in-age exemption for those within four years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p01] However, sexual relations between people 18 or older and people under 18 are illegal if they are in a "significant relationship".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Each U.S. state has its own general age of consent.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] As of August 1, 2018, the age of consent in each state in the United States is either 16 years of age, 17 years of age, or 18 years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The most common age of consent is 16, which is a common age of consent in most other Western countries.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] These state laws are discussed in detail below.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Most of these state laws refer to statutory rape using names other than "statutory rape" in particular.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Such laws may refer to: "carnal knowledge of a minor", "child molestation", "corruption of a minor", "sexual misconduct", or "unlawful carnal knowledge".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The laws of Georgia, Missouri, North Carolina, Mississippi, and Tennessee specifically refer to "statutory rape", with each state defining it differently.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Nevada criminalizes "statutory sexual seduction" while Pennsylvania criminalizes "statutory sexual assault".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In most states there is not a single age in which a person may consent, but rather consent varies depending upon the minimum age of the younger party, the minimum age of the older party, or the differences in age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Some states have a single age of consent.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Thirty U.S. states have age gap laws which make sexual activity legal if the ages of both participants are close to one another, and these laws are often referred to as "Romeo and Juliet laws".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Other states have measures which reduce penalties if the two parties are close in age, and others provide an affirmative defense if the two parties are close in age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Even though state laws regarding the general age of consent and age gap laws differ, it is common for people in the United States to assume that sexual activity with someone under 18 is statutory rape.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] "(a) A person commits the crime of sexual abuse in the second degree if: ...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] "(a) A person commits the crime of rape in the second degree if:...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] "(a) A person commits the crime of sodomy in the first degree if he or she:...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The State Legislature passed *Act 2010-497* making it a crime for any school employee to have any sexual relations with a student under the age of 19.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] A school employee includes a teacher, school administrator, student teacher, safety or resource officer, coach, and other school employee.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Age of the student and consent is not a defense.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] So thus, the age of consent of 16 cannot be used.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] (a) He or she is a school employee and engages in a sex act or deviant sexual intercourse with a student, regardless of whether the student is male or female.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Consent is not a defense to a charge under this section.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] (b) As used in this section, sex act means sexual intercourse with any penetration, however slight; emission is not required.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] (a) He or she is a school employee and engaging in sexual contact with a student, regardless of whether the student is male or female.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] (b) As used in this section, sexual contact means any touching of the sexual or other intimate parts of a student, done for the purpose of gratifying the sexual desire of either party.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The term includes soliciting or harassing a student to perform a sex act.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Any individual convicted of these offenses, regardless if they received prison time or not, will have to register as a Sex Offender for the remainder of their life.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] There was also a law which prohibited K-12 teachers from having sex with students under age 19, and violators could face prison time or get on the sex offender registry.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2017, Alabama Circuit Judge Glenn Thompson, of Morgan County in the north of the state, ruled that this law was unconstitutional.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent is 16, provided the older partner is not in a position of authority.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] However, there exist in the legislation defenses to prosecution if the defendant is close-in-age to the minor or a spouse of the minor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Note: these are not close-in-age exceptions but defenses in court.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent is 16, with some close-in-age exemptions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Details: The minimum age is 16 for anyone age 20 or older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Under 20, the younger person must not be less than 14.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] However, there exists a "sexual indecency with a child" law that prohibits any person over age 18 from soliciting sexual activity from anyone under 15 (or believed to be under 15).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] This means that while sexual activity between a 14-year-old and an 18- or 19-year-old may be legal in and of itself, soliciting it could still be charged as a class D felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Sexual penetration (intercourse or "deviate sexual activity") between a major (18+) and a minor under 14 is a rape, punishable by a minimum 25-year sentence.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Under 18, there is a defense for sexual contact if the younger (<14) minor is not more than 4 years younger if 12 or above, or not more than 3 years younger if under 12.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] For acts involving penetration, the exception is 3 years for all ages below 14.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Subtitle 2 – Offenses Against The Person.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] § 5-14-126 – Sexual assault in the third degree.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] § 5-14-127 – Sexual assault in the fourth degree.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] § 5-14-110 Sexual Indecency With a Child.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Chapter 27 - Juvenile Courts And Proceedings.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In California, there is a crime of "Unlawful sexual intercourse", which is an act of sexual intercourse with a person under the age of 18 who is not the spouse of the person.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] (CA Penal Code § 261.5 (a)) As per the text of the statute, all sexual activity with a person under the age of 18 (and not their spouse) is a criminal offense.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Even if two 17-year-olds willingly have sex with each other, *both* have committed a crime, although it is only a misdemeanor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] There are also civil sanctions possible for a violation stated above.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] There are separate crimes for committing sodomy with minors.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] There are separate crimes for committing any lewd or lascivious act with a person under the age of 14.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent, at the time applying only when the girl is the younger party, was 10 when California introduced its penal code in 1850.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1889 the age of consent was raised to 14.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent in California has been 18 since 1913.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Some media sources reported that the age of consent in California in the 1970s was 14 or 16 but in fact it was and has been 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In the 1990s Governor of California Pete Wilson stated that there was a trend of men in their mid-to-late 20s having sex with and impregnating teenage girls around 14 years of age and that the statutory rape laws needed to be enforced to prevent this.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2012 Kristin Olsen, a Republican member of the State Assembly of California, sponsored a bill that criminalizes sexual relations between K-12 teachers and students, including students over 18, as well as sexual text messages and other communications aimed at seducing a student.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill was proposed after a 41-year-old teacher and 18-year-old high school student publicly announced that they were in a relationship.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill was killed in committee by Democratic lawmakers concerned about the constitutionality of the proposed legislation.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] These civil rulings remain controversial.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent in Colorado is 17; however, there exists in the legislation close-in-age exceptions, which allow those aged 15 and 16 to engage in acts with those less than ten years older and those less than 15 to engage in acts with those less than four years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] A 17-year-old may not, however, consent to sex with a person who is in a position of trust with respect to the person under the age of eighteen.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Notwithstanding the age of consent, however, for purposes of child prostitution offenses in Colorado, a "child" means a person under the age of eighteen years.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Reasonable mistake of age, or similarity in age, is not a defense to these offenses.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] All child prostitution offenses are class three felonies (class one felonies are punishable by life without parole, class two felonies include second degree murder).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The same conduct, entered into with an eighteen-year-old and without a belief that the prostitute was under eighteen years of age, would be a misdemeanor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Those under the age of eighteen are also children for the crime of inducing or coercing someone to have sex or to have sexual conduct with another for the voyeur's gratification, or to expose themselves to another for the voyeur's sexual gratification, C.R.S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] There is a marriage exception to both Colorado's statutory rape law, C.R.S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] 18-3-402, the crime of sexual assault upon a child by a person in a position of trust, C.R.S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] 18-3-405.3, and Colorado's child prostitution laws.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] However, while Colorado law does recognize common law marriages entered into when both spouses are eighteen years of age or older, it does not recognize common law marriages entered into in Colorado or elsewhere after September 1, 2006, when one spouse is under eighteen years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The *general* age of consent in Connecticut is 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Connecticut recognizes that minors who are at least 13 can consent to sexual activity if (and only if) there is less than a 3-year age difference.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] However consensual, sexual intercourse within the 3-year age difference by a minor 13 through 17 years old *may*, upon a complaint, lead the Connecticut Superior Court to a "family with service needs" finding.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Such a finding would allow the Court to issue orders as it finds necessary in dealing with the matter.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Consensual sexual intercourse over the 3-year age difference (where the minor is 13 to 15 years old) would subject the older party to a charge of Sexual Assault, 2nd Degree, in violation of *C.G.S. § 53a-71(a)(1)*.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Any juvenile offender 14 years old or older has the case automatically transferred to the regular criminal docket of the Superior Court by operation of law, and thus stands before the court to be tried as an adult.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] A guilty verdict would result in conviction of a Class B felony sex offense, with a mandatory minimum of 9 months and maximum 20 years imprisonment.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] It would *not* matter if the older person did not know of the age difference, or if the younger person lied about age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] However, if the offender is 17 years old or younger, has a clean record, and such sexual activity was consensual, Youthful Offender status (a pre-trial diversionary program that seals the court record and results in a dismissal of charges) *may* be granted.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Previously the Connecticut age gap was two years, not three.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2007 there had been a proposal to increase the gap to four years to reduce the number of close-in-age statutory rape cases being prosecuted, but three years was selected as a compromise.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Connecticut also recognizes that minors *under* 13 are released from *criminal liability* as to consensual sexual activity if (and only if) there is less than a 2-year age difference.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Consensual (between minors) sexual intercourse over the 2-year age difference (where the minor is under 13 years old) would subject the older minor to a charge of Sexual Assault, 1st Degree, in violation of *C.G.S. § 53a-70(a)(2)*.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] A guilty verdict would result in conviction of a Class A felony sex offense, with a mandatory minimum of 5–10 years and maximum 25 years imprisonment.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] However, the offender would have the same chance to apply for Youthful Offender status (see *Sexual Assault, 2nd Degree* above) provided the criteria are met.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] This is a class B felony, and there is no close in age exception, nor is there a requirement that the actor be over 18 years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] A juvenile offender 13 years old and younger would be charged as a "serious juvenile offender" under *C.G.S. § 46b-120(12)(A)*.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Because the charge is a sex offense, the juvenile prosecutor can request that the proceeding designated a "serious sexual offender prosecution".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Unless the juvenile waives the right to a trial by jury, the case proceeds to the regular criminal docket of the Superior Court, where the juvenile must face trial as an adult.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] If the juvenile agrees to the waiver, the case will proceed through the juvenile system with a bench trial.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent in Delaware is 18, but it is legal for teenagers aged 16 and 17 to engage in sexual intercourse as long as the older partner is younger than 30.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Rape in the fourth degree; class C felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] (a) A person is guilty of rape in the fourth degree when the person: ...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] However, in 2009 Senate Bill 185 amended the text of article 768 from anyone under 16 years to anyone under 18 years.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] § 768 Unlawful sexual contact in the second degree; class F felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] 762(d)specifies a close-in-age "affirmative defense" for 12- to 15-year-olds.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Sexual conduct pursuant to this section will not be a crime.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] This affirmative defense will not apply if the victim had not yet reached that victim's twelfth birthday at the time of the act.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent in Florida is 18, but close-in-age exemptions exist.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] By law, the exception permits a person 23 years of age or younger to engage in legal sexual activity with a minor aged 16 or 17.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] 794.05 Unlawful sexual activity with certain minors.-- (1) A person 24 years of age or older who engages in sexual activity with a person 16 or 17 years of age commits a felony of the second degree, punishable as provided in s.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] As used in this section, "sexual activity" means oral, anal, or vaginal penetration by, or union with, the sexual organ of another; however, sexual activity does not include an act done for a bona fide medical purpose.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] It is illegal to have non-penetrative sexual contact with a person under 16, and there are no close-in-age exceptions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] If the offender is 18+ it is a 2nd degree felony, and if the offender is under 18 it is a 3rd degree felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] It is a third degree felony for a person 24 or older to have non-penetrative sexual contact with a person 16 or 17 years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] A law passed in 2007, as amended, states that people convicted of certain sex crimes involving children may be removed from the sex offender list if they were no more than four years older than their victims, had only that offense on their records, and had victims aged 13–17.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent in Georgia is 16 and there is no close-in-age exception, though the offenses are a misdemeanor rather than a felony in cases where the perpetrator is less than 19 years of age *and* is no more than 4 years older than the victim.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The crime of "*statutory rape*" makes it illegal for a perpetrator of any age to have sexual intercourse with someone under the age of 16 that they are not married to.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] This law specifies that a defendant cannot be convicted on the testimony of the victim alone; some other evidence must be present.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] This offense carries a minimum sentence of 1 year in prison, and a maximum of 20 years.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] If the offender is 21 years of age or older, the minimum is raised to 10 years in prison, and the offender is subject to sex offender sentencing guidelines.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] However, if the victim is 14 or 15 years old and the actor is age 18 or younger and within 4 years of the victim's age, the crime is reduced to a misdemeanor with a maximum sentence of 1 year in prison.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] It carries a minimum sentence of 5 years and a max of 20 years in prison for a first-time offender, as well as mandatory counseling and sex offender sentencing guidelines.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] For repeat offenders, the minimum 10 years and the maximum is life imprisonment.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] This crime has the same close-in-age exception as *statutory rape* stated above if the victim is 14 or 15 years old and the actor is 18 or younger and within 4 years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] A third applicable crime is "*aggravated child molestation*", which is any act of the previously mentioned *child molestation* that causes injuries to the victim, or involves an act of "sodomy" (defined under state law as any act of oral sex or anal sex).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] This crime carries a sentence of 25 years to life, and lifetime probation thereafter.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] However, if the victim is 13, 14 or 15 years old, the actor is 18 or younger and within 4 years of age, and the act committed was "sodomy" and did not cause injury, the crime is reduced to a misdemeanor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] This exception was added after a landmark case, Wilson v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] State of Georgia occurred in 2006 and caused lawmakers to think the statute should have a close-in-age exception.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] At the time because of the words of the law, a 17-year-old man was sentenced to 10 years in prison for having consensual oral sex with a 15-year-old girl.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2005, a bill was proposed before the Georgia General Assembly to raise the age of consent from 16 to 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Georgia was resistant to raising its age of consent in the Progressive Era.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1894, the Georgia Supreme Court reversed the conviction of a man convicted of raping a 10-year-old girl because the age of consent in Georgia was 10 at the time.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Nonetheless, the Court recommended raising the Georgia age of consent, saying "the age of consent in many States is higher than in this State, and should be made higher here; and a committee of ladies" is petitioning to do that.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] As it turned out, Georgia's age of consent remained at 10 until 1918, when it was raised to 14.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] After the 1918 law changes, Georgia still had the lowest age of consent in the country, because all 47 other states had raised their ages of consent to 16 or 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The Georgia age of consent remained at 14 until 1995, when a bill proposed by Steve Langford to make 16 the age of consent passed.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] There is a close-in-age exemption, which allows those aged 14 and 15 to consent to sex with those less than five years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In the 1990s the age of consent was 14, the lowest in the United States.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Avery Chumbley, a member of the Hawaiian Senate, had made efforts to raise the age of consent since 1996.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent was changed to 16 by Act 1, House Bill 236, passed by the Legislature of Hawaii in 2001.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Hawaii first established age of consent for contact/penetration as 10/14 years old in 1869 which lasted until 1912.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The legal status from 1913 to 1924 is unclear, but by 1925 it was set to the higher numbers of 12/16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In both sets of laws these penalties only penalized males contacting females.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1974 the laws were changed to add the additional requirement that there was a "reckless infliction" of "serious" bodily harm.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] This requirement was removed in 1986 and the wording was changed to apply to persons of any gender, not only males.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Age of consent in Illinois is 17, and rises to 18 with someone who has a position of authority or trust over the victim.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] There is no close-in-age exception, crossing the age boundary is *Criminal Sexual Assault*.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Any sexual contact of minors between the ages of 9 and 16 is *Criminal sexual abuse*.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] When the victim is younger than 9 and the perpetrator 13 to 16, the crime becomes *Aggravated Criminal Sexual Assault*; when the victim is younger than 13 and the perpetrator 17 or older, it becomes *Predatory criminal sexual assault of a child*.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Sex with a victim with severe intellectual disability at any age, or with a family or household member under 18, is *Aggravated criminal sexual abuse*, though penetration upgrades it to *Aggravated Criminal Sexual Assault*.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Although Illinois' minimum marriage age (with parental consent or court order) is 16, there is no statutory exception to the age of sexual consent.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Bill 1139 was introduced in 2011 to decriminalize sexual relationships between children 13–16 years old and those fewer than five years older, but the bill failed to pass.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2011 a bill was proposed that would allow people who violated the age of consent laws and were close in age with their victims to petition a judge to be removed from the sex offender registry.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] This bill, HB 1139, was, written by Republican Party state representative Robert Pritchard.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] An editorial in the *Chicago Sun-Times* argued in favor of the bill.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Emily McAsey, a Democratic state representative from Lockport, stated opposition to the idea, citing that she was "troubled" by the idea of a romantic relationship between a 14-year-old and an 18-year-old.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Republican state representative Dennis Reboletti of Elmhurst stated that he did not believe judges should be able to reverse decisions made by prosecutors.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill passed the Illinois House Judiciary II Committee 4–3 in February 2011 and moved to the Illinois Senate.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2012 Democratic state senator William Haine of Alton sponsored Senate Bill 3359 which included a provision that a person who had sex with a minor between 13 and 17 while he/she was fewer than five years older may petition to be removed from the sex offender registry after serving 10 years.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Haine stated that he did not want "Romeo and Juliet" offenders to be on the sex offender registry.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] A close-in-age exception allows minors 14–15 years of age to legally consent to sex with a partner who is less than 18 years old.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Under certain aggravating circumstances, the offense increases to a Class B felony or to a Class A felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The law allows the actor a defense to prosecution if the victim is currently or was previously married (the absolute minimum marriageable age in Indiana is 16), although this defense does not apply in the case of violence, threats or drugs.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The law also allows a defense if the actor is within 4 years of age of the younger person *and* the two were in an ongoing dating/romantic relationship.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] This is not a close-in-age exception though, but merely a defense in court.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The law also allows a mistake of age defense if the actor reasonably believed the victim was 16 or older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age limit rises to 18, according to IC35-42-4-7, if the actor is an adult who is the guardian, adoptive parent, adoptive grandparent, custodian, or stepparent of the minor; or a child care worker for the minor; or a military recruiter who is attempting to enlist over the minor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Any person who engages in sexual intercourse with a child under 14 years of age commits a Class B felony, under *IC 35-42-4-3 Child molesting*.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Under certain aggravating circumstances, the crime becomes a Class A felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent in Iowa is 16, with a close-in-age exemption for those aged 14 and 15, who may engage in sexual acts with partners less than 4 years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Section 709.4 states: *A person commits sexual abuse in the third degree when the person performs a sex act under any of the following circumstances ...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] 2(c) The other person is fourteen or fifteen years of age and any of the following are true ...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] 21-5507 allows for a lesser penalty if the minor is 14 or 15 and the offender is under 19 years old.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] 21-5506 covers indecent liberties with a child and aggravated indecent liberties with a child.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Aggravated indecent liberties with a child is sexual intercourse with a child who is 14 or more years of age but less than 16 years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Limon (2005) the previous Kansas age of consent law, which did not apply to homosexuals, was struck down by the Kansas Supreme Court due to 2003's Lawrence v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Consensual sex with persons at least age 16 but not yet 18 is permitted only if the actor is less than 10 years older than the younger party.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Kentucky Revised Statutes (KRS) § 510.020 deems a person unable to consent if they are less than 16 years old, or if they are age 16 or 17 and the other party is at least 10 years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Sexual abuse in the first degree is a Class D felony if the victim is 12 to 17 years old, and a Class C felony if the victim is under 12.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] However, KRS § 510.120(2) provides a defense to prosecutions under § 510.120(1)(b) (where the actor is between ages 18 and 21) for sexual abuse in the second degree if the victim is at least 14 and the actor is less than 5 years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Similarly, it is a defense to the Class B misdemeanor of "sexual abuse in the third degree" (KRS § 510.130), defined as subjecting another person to non-consensual sex, if the lack of consent was due solely to incapacity by age, the victim is 14 or 15 years old, and the actor is under 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Teenagers aged 14 and 15 may engage in sexual intercourse with partners who are less than 5 years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] A person is guilty of sexual abuse of a minor if: A.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The person engages in a sexual act with another person, not the actor's spouse, who is either 14 or 15 years of age and the actor is at least 5 years older than the other person.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In Maryland, *sexual offense* (1st & 2nd degree) and *rape* (1st & 2nd degree) carry the same penalty.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The distinction is that a *rape* involves vaginal intercourse.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent in Massachusetts is 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Whoever commits any unnatural and lascivious act with a child under the age of sixteen shall be punished ...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] However, Chapter 272, Section 4 sets another age of consent at 18 when the victim is "of chaste life" and the perpetrator induces them to have "unlawful" sexual intercourse.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent in Michigan is 16, unless one is an authority figure in which case the age of consent is 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] 750.520d Criminal sexual conduct in the third degree; felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] (1) A person is guilty of criminal sexual conduct in the third degree if the person engages in sexual penetration with another person and if any of the following circumstances exist: (a) That other person is at least 13 years of age and under 16 years of age ...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In March 2012 the Michigan Senate passed a bill which was to prohibit sexual relations between students of any age and teachers.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] If the actor is in a position of authority, the age of consent is 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Children under age 16 are considered incapable of consent (but it is a lesser offense if the older party is less than 36 months older).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] If the younger party is 13, 14 or 15, the other person must be no more than 24 months older for acts of penetration, and 48 months older for sexual activity not amounting to penetration.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The specifics of these laws are covered under Sections 609.34x of the Minnesota Criminal Code.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent in Mississippi is 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] (1) A person is guilty of sexual battery if he or she engages in sexual penetration with: ...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] (c) A child at least fourteen (14) but under sixteen (16) years of age, if the person is thirty-six (36) or more months older than the child ...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] There is a 4-year "close in age" exception for minors aged 14–16, but NO exception for those aged 13 or below.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Mistake as to the age of the victim may be a defense in some circumstances.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Statutory rape and sodomy involve a victim less than 14 years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] Statutory rape and sodomy in the second degree involve a victim less than 17 years of age and an accused who is 21 years of age or older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The crime of child molestation in the fourth degree occurs when a person, "being more than 4 years older than the child less than 17 years of age, subjects the child to sexual contact".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] While the statutory titles are cast in terms of Rape and Sodomy, the statutes prohibit conduct that is described as "sexual intercourse" and "deviant sexual intercourse".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] The age of consent in Montana is 16 per Montana Code Annotated (2019) section 45-5-625(c).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p02] In addition Nebraska has a law prohibiting "lewdly inducing" a person under 17 to "carnally know" any other person.
