[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (4) In any prosecution under this section, the age of the actor shall be an essential element of the offense that must be proved beyond a reasonable doubt.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] The age of consent in New Hampshire is 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Sexual penetration with a person at least 13 but younger than 16 years old is always illegal, but is only a misdemeanor if the age difference is under 4 years, and in that case the "offender" is not required to register as a sex offender.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Sexual contact (without penetration) is legal between those 13–15 years of age and partners less than 5 years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] However, if the partner is acting "in loco parentis", e.g. as a teacher or a guardian, the minimum age is 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] If the victim is *less than 18* and the partner is a parent, guardian, sibling or any other person closer than a fourth cousin or has any type of authority over the victim (for example, a teacher) then the assailant may be charged with a crime.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] For instance, it's criminal for a manager of any age to have sex with a 16 or 17-year-old subordinate, even if the sex is consensual.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] State law implies (by not saying anything) that minors between 13 and 15 years old may, in general, engage in a consensual sexual relationship with someone up to four years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Therefore, for example, it is legal for a 14-year-old male or female to engage in consensual sex with a person up to 18 years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Specifically, NJ state law details three circumstances of sexual assault under which the age of consent is pertinent.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Simple sexual assault (a crime of the second degree) is defined in two ways, according to N.J.S.A 2C:14-2(b).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] First, a person must have committed sexual contact (that is, intentional touching of intimate parts for sexual gratification) while the victim was under 13 and the assailant was over four years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] or (2) the victim was between 13 and 15 and the assailant was over four years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] In a period before 1979 the age of consent was raised to 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] In May 1979 the New Jersey Legislature passed a bill sponsored by Christopher Jackman, the assembly speaker, changed the age of consent to 13.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] This bill was scheduled to go into effect on September 1, 1979.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] By June 1979 there were reports Governor of New Jersey Brendan T.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Byrne had refused to sign the bill into law.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] The coordinator for New Jersey Majority Women, Elizabeth Sadowski, asked for a postponement of this bill.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] The age of consent for penetrative sexual activity in New Mexico is 16 with age gap, marital, and school employee provisions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] New Mexico Code > Chapter 30 > Article 9 > Section 30-9-11: Criminal sexual penetration.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] This was also confirmed by the Supreme Court of New Mexico in *Perez v State (1990)*, in which it was determined that mistake of age may be a potential defense to charges of criminal sexual penetration where the victim is over 13 years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] The court stated; "The fact that knowledge of a child's age is not an essential element of the crime does not dispose of defendant's argument that mistake of fact may be raised as a defense.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] It simply means that the state does not have to prove defendant knew the victim **was under the age of sixteen**.
