[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] 30-6-3 stipulates the crime of "contributing to the delinquency of minor" for any act or omission of duty that causes or tends to cause the delinquency of any person under 18 years.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] It is a 4th degree felony, but not a sexual offense.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] "Sex", as used above, refers to the four conspicuous types of sexual acts, including "sexual intercourse", "oral sexual conduct" (both types), and "anal sexual conduct".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] The latter three acts were known by statute as "deviant sexual intercourse" prior to 2003.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Non-intercourse sexual activity is also regulated based on age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Non-intercourse sexual activity, called "sexual contact" is defined as "*any touching of the sexual or other intimate parts of a person not married to the actor for the purpose of gratifying sexual desire of either party.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] It includes the touching of the actor by the victim, as well as the touching of the victim by the actor, whether directly or through clothing.*" (NY Penal Law § 130.00[3].) If the person is underage such "sexual contact" can constitute the crime of "sexual abuse".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] It is *not* a defense that the perpetrator believed the victim was older than is later proven.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Legally recognized marriage *is* a defense.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Someone under that age may be adjudicated a juvenile delinquent, but may not commit these crimes.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] On the other hand, someone who is 16 years old commits a crime by voluntarily having sex with anyone who cannot themselves legally consent to sex, including another 16-year-old, even if this "victim" is actually older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] 1976]; *Matter of Jessie C.*, 164 A.D.2d 731; 565 N.Y.S.2d 941 [4 Dept., 1991].) In effect, mutual crimes are committed when two unmarried 16-year-old individuals voluntarily have sex with each other in New York State, each being the "victim" of the other.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] It appears that the crime of "Predatory sexual assault against a child", a class A-II felony, effectively subsumes all instances of "statutory" first degree rape/criminal sexual act where the victim is under 13 (NY Penal Law §§ 130.35[4], 130.50[4]) and the perpetrator over 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (NY Penal Law § 130.96.) Thus, any person who commits one of these lesser offenses would necessarily commit the greater offense of "Predatory sexual assault against a child." (*See, People v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] There are other special offenses, namely "Course of sexual conduct against a child in the first degree" and "Course of sexual conduct against a child in the second degree" that punish sex with an underage person combined with an additional illegal sexual act during wide time periods.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] These do not subject a person to more punishment than the crimes listed above but provide only a gimmick for prosecutors to avoid the requirement that an individual sex act be specified in a rape indictment.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (Note that "violent felonies" are specified by NY Penal Law § 70.02.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] The age of consent in North Carolina is 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] However, certain exceptions to this general rule exist.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] No employee of a K-12 school can have any sexual activity with any student at that school except when married to the person {§ 14‑27.7}; this is a felony unless the actor is less than 4 years older than the student and is not a teacher, administrator, student teacher, safety officer, or coach.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] This prohibition covers adults and students who were at the school at the same time, and continues in force as long as the younger person is a student at any K-12 school, regardless of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Any sexual intercourse with a person under 16 years of age is prohibited unless the defendant is less than 4 years older than the victim except when married to the person {§ 14‑27.2, 14‑27.4 & 14‑27.7A}.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (a) A defendant is guilty of a Class B1 felony if the defendant engages in vaginal intercourse or a sexual act with another person who is 13, 14, or 15 years old and the defendant is at least six years older than the person, except when the defendant is lawfully married to the person.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] The age of consent in North Dakota is 18, with a close-in-age exemption for minors aged 15–17 as long as the older partner is less than three years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] An adult who solicits with the intent to engage in a sexual act with a minor under age fifteen or engages in or causes another to engage in a sexual act when the adult is at least twenty-two years of age and the victim is a minor fifteen years of age or older, is guilty of a class C felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Sexual assault.*, an adult who has sexual contact with or causes someone else to have sexual contact with a person under the age of 18 is guilty of a class C felony if the adult is at least 22 years of age, or class A misdemeanor if the adult is aged 18–21.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] In North Dakota law, "minor" refers to individuals under the age of 18 and "adult" refers to individuals aged 18 or older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] The age of consent in Ohio is 16 as specified by Section 2907.04 of the Ohio Revised Code.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] However, there exists a close-in-age exception where a minor 13 or older can consent to sex as long as their partner is also at least 13 but less than 18 years old.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] 2907.04 Unlawful sexual conduct with minor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (A) No person who is eighteen years of age or older shall engage in sexual conduct with another, who is not the spouse of the offender, when the offender knows the other person is thirteen years of age or older but less than sixteen years of age, or the offender is reckless in that regard.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (B) Whoever violates this section is guilty of unlawful sexual conduct with a minor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (1) Except as otherwise provided in divisions (B)(2), (3), and (4) of this section, unlawful sexual conduct with a minor is a felony of the fourth degree.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (2) Except as otherwise provided in division (B)(4) of this section, if the offender is less than four years older than the other person, unlawful sexual conduct with a minor is a misdemeanor of the first degree.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (3) Except as otherwise provided in division (B)(4) of this section, if the offender is ten or more years older than the other person, unlawful sexual conduct with a minor is a felony of the third degree.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (4) If the offender previously has been convicted of or pleaded guilty to a violation of section 2907.02, 2907.03, or 2907.04 of the Revised Code or a violation of former section 2907.12 of the Revised Code, unlawful sexual conduct with a minor is a felony of the second degree.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Non-penetrative sexual contact is permitted between 13- to 15-year-olds and anyone less than 4 years older, even if the older person is 18 or older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (A) No person shall have sexual contact with another, not the spouse of the offender; cause another, not the spouse of the offender, to have sexual contact with the offender; or cause two or more other persons to have sexual contact when any of the following applies...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] four or more years older than such other person.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] It is illegal for a person of any age to have sex with a child beneath 13 years of age who they are not married to.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] No person shall engage in sexual conduct with another who is not the spouse of the offender or who is the spouse of the offender but is living separate and apart from the offender when any of the following applies ...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] However, the preceding statute, Section 2907.03, specifies that sexual conduct between anyone under 18 and a teacher, administrator, or coach of the school they attend, a cleric, or other person in authority, is punishable as a felony of the third degree.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (5) The offender is the other person's natural or adoptive parent, or a stepparent, or guardian, custodian, or person in loco parentis of the other person.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (8) The other person is a minor, the offender is a teacher, administrator, coach, or other person in authority employed by or serving in an institution of higher education, and the other person is enrolled in or attends that institution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (9) The other person is a minor, and the offender is the other person's athletic or other type of coach, is the other person's instructor, is the leader of a scouting troop of which the other person is a member, or is a person with temporary or occasional disciplinary control over the other person.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] (12) The other person is a minor, the offender is a cleric, and the other person is a member of, or attends, the church or congregation served by the cleric.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Laws against "contributing to the unruliness or delinquency of a child" (§ 2919.24) and "interference with custody" (§ 2919.23) may be used against those who have sex with those who are 16 and 17 if a parent or guardian complains.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] These two crimes are not considered to be sexual offenses.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] In 1989 Donald Edgar Lukens was prosecuted under the misdemeanor charge "contributing to the delinquency and unruliness of a child" for having sex with a 16-year-old girl.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] At the time he was 58 years old, and he received a 30-day jail sentence.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p03] Romeo and Juliet laws apply to minors aged 16 or older if the older person is not more than 4 years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Sexual offenses are defined under the Oregon Revised Statutes Chapter 163.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] With regards to age only, the following offenses are defined.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Additionally, Oregon has a three-year rule defined under ORS 163.345.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] However, this does not apply to Rape 1, or Sodomy 1, effectively limiting the age to 12.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] However, a person within the three-year limit can still be charged with Sexual Misconduct (Class C Misdemeanor) under ORS 163.445, if the victim was under 15 years of age (163.345(3)).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent in Pennsylvania is 16 years of age for sexual consent.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent was lowered from 16 to 14 in 1976 and was increased back to 16 in 1995.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Under current Pennsylvania law, teenagers aged 13, 14 and 15 may or may not be able to legally engage in sexual activity with partners who are less than 4 years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Such partners could not be prosecuted under statutory rape laws, but may be liable for other offenses, even when the sexual activity is consensual.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] In December 2011 the Pennsylvania Legislature passed an amendment stating that an employee of a school who engages in sexual relations with any student or athletic player under the age of 18 may receive a third-degree felony charge.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] In 2014 Governor of Pennsylvania Tom Corbett signed into law an amendment making this law apply to athletic coaches who work outside of an educational setting.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Historically Pennsylvania prosecutors were only allowed to issue misdemeanor charges such as corruption of minors against teachers and coaches who had sex with 16 and 17-year-old students.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] In addition to the corruption of minors charge, Pennsylvania prosecutors have also brought child endangerment charges against schoolteachers who had sex with 16 and 17-year-old students.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Under Pennsylvania law, a defendant is strictly liable for the offense of rape, a felony of the first degree, when the complainant is 12 or younger.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Pennsylvania has enacted several other strict liability sexual offenses when the complainant is under 16, but 13 years old or older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] (7) the complainant is less than 13 years of age; or (8) the complainant is less than 16 years of age and the person is four or more years older than the complainant and the complainant and the person are not married to each other.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] (b) Aggravated indecent assault of a child.--A person commits aggravated indecent assault of a child when the person violates subsection (a)(1), (2), (3), (4), (5) or (6) and the complainant is less than 13 years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] (7) who is less than 16 years of age and the person is four or more years older than the complainant and the complainant and person are not married to each other.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The question of whether consensual intercourse with a minor 16 years or older tends to corrupt the morals of that minor is a jury question to be decided by the "common sense of the community".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] (2) Open lewdness as defined in section 5901 (relating to open lewdness).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] (3) Prostitution as defined in section 5902 (relating to prostitution and related offenses).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] (4) Obscene and other sexual materials and performances as defined in section 5903 (relating to obscene and other sexual materials and performances).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] (5) Sexual abuse of children as defined in section 6312 (relating to sexual abuse of children).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] (6) Sexual exploitation of children as defined in section 6320 (relating to sexual exploitation of children).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] There is also a *corruption of minors* statute against adults corrupting the morals of minors under 18 years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] However, the corruption of minors statute only applies to perpetrators 18 years of age and older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent in Rhode Island is 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Sexual intercourse with a minor aged 14–15 by an actor 18 or older is third degree sexual assault, sexual intercourse with a minor under the age of 14 by an actor of any age is child molestation.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] However, there is a close-in-age exception that allows people aged 16–17 to have sex with a minor aged 14 or 15, but not younger.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Non-penetrative activity with minors 14 and younger constitutes second degree child molestation.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent in South Carolina is 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Criminal sexual conduct: definitions ...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] (2) the actor engages in sexual battery with a victim who is at least fourteen years of age but who is less than sixteen years of age and the actor is in a position of familial, custodial, or official authority to coerce the victim to submit or is older than the victim.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] However, a person may not be convicted of a violation of the provisions of this item if he is eighteen years of age or less when he engages in consensual sexual conduct with another person who is at least fourteen years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] However, a person may not be convicted of a violation of the provisions of this subsection if the person is eighteen years of age or less when the person engages in consensual lewd or lascivious conduct with another person who is at least fourteen years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent in South Dakota is 16 and there is no close-in-age exemption, although if the perpetrator is within three years of age of the victim or is under 18 the penalties are reduced.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Rape is an act of sexual penetration accomplished with any person under any of the following circumstances: ...
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] (5)If the victim is thirteen years of age, but less than sixteen years of age, and the perpetrator is at least three years older than the victim.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Sexual contact with child under sixteen—Felony or misdemeanor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Any person, sixteen years of age or older, who knowingly engages in sexual contact with another person, other than that person's spouse if the other person is under the age of sixteen years is guilty of a Class 3 felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] If the actor is less than three years older than the other person, the actor is guilty of a Class 1 misdemeanor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] If an adult has a previous conviction for a felony violation of this section, any subsequent felony conviction for a violation under this section, is a Class 2 felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Notwithstanding § 23A-42-2, a charge brought pursuant to this section may be commenced at any time before the victim becomes age twenty-five or within seven years of the commission of the crime, whichever is longer.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Sexual contact with child under sixteen years of age—Violation as misdemeanor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Any person, younger than sixteen years of age, who knowingly engages in sexual contact with another person, other than his or her spouse, if such other person is younger than sixteen years of age, is guilty of a Class 1 misdemeanor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] A close-in-age exemption allows minors aged 13–17 to engage in sexual penetration with partners less than 4 years older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Penalties differ depending on the age of the minor, as well as the age difference between the minor and the offender.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Aside from situations involving a position of authority, the only age limit for non-penetrative sexual contact appears to be 13.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent in Texas is 17, though there is a specific law targeting "sexual performance", which requires a visual representation (like a video or a part in a play).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] A Texas court case decision, Ex parte Fujisaka, argued that these two laws, specifying different ages below which a sexual act may be considered a criminal act, are to be treated independently of each other.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Section 43.25(b) *Sexual Performance by a Minor* makes it a crime to employ, authorize, or induce a child younger than 18 years of age to engage in a sexual performance or to engage in sexual conduct without any requirement of performance.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] A parent or legal guardian or custodian of a child younger than 18 years of age commits an offense if he/she consents to the participation by the child in a sexual performance.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] When inducement is an element of 43.25(b), it is not required that there be a threat, promise of payment or other specific incentive or even verbal persuasion for the inducement to be proven.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Some confusion arises regarding the applicability of section 43.25 to mere "sexual conduct", due to the section title "sexual performance by a child" and other provisions that seem to suggest that the intention of this section is to criminalize commercial sexual performances by a minor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] However, in John Perry Dornbusch, Appellant, v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The State of Texas as well as in *Summers v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] State*, 11-92-057-CR, 845 S.W.2d 440 (1992), the decisions support the interpretation that section 43.25(b) is not limited to cases involving "sexual performance" as defined by section 43.25(a)(1).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] No age is specified by the statute (thus, even if the student has reached the age of consent, it is still a violation), and violations are a second degree felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] People convicted under 21.12 do not have to register as sex offenders.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The law exists to prevent scenarios where a teacher or employee coerces a student into a sexual relationship in exchange for higher grades or other favors.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] In 2003, Helen Giddings, a Democratic member of the Texas House of Representatives, first authored the anti student-teacher sex bill but only intended for it to take effect if the student is 17 or younger.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Warren Chisum of Pampa removed the maximum age from the bill.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Shortly after the law passed, a teacher engaged in sexual intercourse with her 18-year-old student, and a Texas court refused to indict her.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] In 2011, an amendment made it illegal for a teacher to having sexual relations with any student in the teacher's school district, not just the teacher's school.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Afterwards, criminal prosecutions of teachers in relationships with students going to other schools in the same school district, including teachers of other educational levels, began occurring.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] In Utah, the minimum age to consent to sexual conduct is 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] (All ages mentioned are "at the time of the act".) Under the Romeo & Juliet exception, it is legal for minors aged 16 and 17 to engage in consensual sexual conduct with partners who are less than 7 years older, and up to 10 years older if the older reasonably didn't know the minor's age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Unlawful sexual conduct with a 16- or 17-year-old.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Effective August 5, 2018: Here "minor" means an individual who is 16 years of age or older, but younger than 18 years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Effective August 5, 2018: Here, a "minor" is an individual who is 14 years of age or older, but younger than 16 years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Effective September 5, 2017: Here, "Adolescent" means a person in the transitional phase of human physical and psychological growth and development between childhood and adulthood who is 12 years of age or older, but under 18 years of age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] "Unlawful adolescent sexual activity" means sexual activity between adolescents under circumstances not amounting to rape, rape of a child, object rape, object rape of a child, forcible sodomy, sodomy on a child, aggravated sexual assault, sexual abuse of a child, or incest.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] 2. where the person is less than 19 years old, the child is at least 15 years old, and the sexual act is consensual.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] However it rises to 18 if the person is related to the minor or in a position of authority over him.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] (d) No person shall engage in a sexual act with a child who is under the age of 18 and is entrusted to the actor's care by authority of law or is the actor's child, grandchild, foster child, adopted child, or stepchild.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent in Virginia is 18, with a close-in-age exception that allows teenagers aged 15 to 17 to engage in sexual acts but only with a partner younger than 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The legal age for non-penetrative sexual contact is 15.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Section § 18.2-63 of the Code refers to minors younger than 15, while § 18.2-371 is about 15-, 16- and 17-year-olds.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Consensual sex where one partner is 15, 16 or 17 and the other is over 18 is a class 1 misdemeanor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Causing or encouraging acts rendering children delinquent, abused, etc.; penalty; abandoned infant.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] As of 2013 the state was attempting to prosecute a 47-year-old man who had oral sex with a 17-year-old girl with a "crimes against nature" law, an anti-sodomy which forbids people from engaging in anal and oral sex and makes these acts a felony offense.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The 47-year-old had been convicted under a misdemeanor offense and his lawyers did not challenge that conviction.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] In addition, the man had to serve one year in prison and register as a sex offender due to the sodomy charge.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Court of Appeals overturned the sodomy conviction, saying it was unconstitutional according to the 2003 *Lawrence v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Attorney General of Virginia Ken Cuccinelli asked the U.S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Supreme Court to do a rehearing, arguing that the state's sodomy laws may still constitutionally apply to 16- and 17-year-olds.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] In October of that year the Supreme Court denied the petition.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent in Washington is 16 with exceptions under different circumstances.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] RCW 9A.44.096 identifies situations in which the age of consent is higher.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent is 18 for sex between foster parents and their foster children.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] It is 21 for sex between school teachers or administration employees and their students.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] It is 18 where the older person is 5 years or more older and in a significant relationship with the younger person and abuses that relationship to have the sexual contact.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] There are also laws restricting immoral communication with persons under 18, but they do not affect the effective age of consent because they apply only to communications for the purpose of committed in illegal sexual act.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] This was decided in rulings by the Washington Court of Appeals and the Washington Supreme Court in the cases of *State v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The following act affected laws around underage sexual activity (sexting), but the age of consent for sexual activity was unaffected.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] A minor 13 to 17 selling sexual content of themselves is now a misdemeanor, and selling sexual content of another minor is a felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Noel Frame sponsored the legislation; it was signed into law on April 24.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Before the passage of the act, possession of any explicit images of anyone under 18 could be treated as a felony and/or require sex offender registration.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent in West Virginia is 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] (2) The person, being sixteen years old or more, engages in sexual intercourse or sexual intrusion with another person who is less than sixteen years old and who is at least four years younger than the defendant and is not married to the defendant.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent in Wisconsin is 18 and there is no close-in-age exception.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] There is, however, a marital exception which allows a person to have sex with a minor 16 or older if they are married to the minor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] If the minor is below 16 both sexual intercourse and any sexual contact are a felony; sexual intercourse with a minor 16–17 by a perpetrator who is not married to the minor is a Class A misdemeanor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] However, Wisconsin has a child enticement law that prohibits people of any age from taking people under 18 to a private area such as a room and exposing a sex organ to them or having the minor expose their sex organ to them.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] 948.09 Sexual intercourse with a child age 16 or older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Whoever has sexual intercourse with a child who is not the defendant's spouse and who has attained the age of 16 years is guilty of a Class A misdemeanor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] ( ... ) (2) Second degree sexual assault.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Whoever has sexual contact or sexual intercourse with a person who has not attained the age of 16 years is guilty of a Class C felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] If the minor is below 16 marriage to the minor by the accused is not a defense.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] 948.02(4) Marriage not a bar to prosecution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] A defendant shall not be presumed to be incapable of violating this section because of marriage to the complainant.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Sexual intercourse with a child younger than 13 carries the highest penalties, it is a Class B felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] 948.02 (e) Whoever has sexual contact with a child who has not attained the age of 13 years is guilty of a class b felony.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] State, the Wyoming Supreme Court held that sexual activity with minors aged 16 or 17 could be charged under Section 14-3-105 of Wyoming Statutes.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] It is an offense in American Samoa to engage in sexual acts with a person under the age of 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent in the Northern Mariana Islands is 16, according to Sections 1306–1309 of the Commonwealth Code.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] There is a close-in-age exemption permitting minors below age 16 to engage in sexual activity with those *less than three years* older.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Under the same provisions, it is also illegal for any person aged 16 or older to aid, encourage, induce or cause minors under 13 to engage in any sexual contact with anyone else, or minors aged 13–15 and at least 3 years younger than the offender to engage in sexual penetration with another person.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent rises to 18 when the older partner – being age 18 or older – is the parent, stepparent, adopted parent, or legal guardian of the younger person, or when the older partner has or occupies a position of authority over the younger person.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] This does not apply for minors aged 16 or 17 as long as the older partner is *less than three years* older and is not the younger person's parent, stepparent, adopted parent or legal guardian.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] According to Section 1310, affirmative defenses for the crimes outlined in Sections 1306–1309 exists for consensual activity between legal spouses and for cases where the defendant reasonably believed that a minor age 13 or older was of legal age.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] The age of consent in Puerto Rico is 16.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Paraphrasing Virgin Islands Code: V.I.C. § 1700–1709 Virgin Islands Code and appeals records Francis vs.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] VI *NOTE: "mistake of fact as to the victim's age is not a defense".* The age of consent is 18.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] There is however a close-in-age exemption that allows minors 16 and 17 years old to consent with someone no more than five years older than themselves and minors 13 to 15 years old to consent with one another, but not with anyone 16 or over.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] *Aggravated rape in the first degree* bans sexual intercourse or sodomy with a child under 13.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Baker Island, Howland Island, Jarvis Island, Johnston Atoll, Kingman Reef, Palmyra Atoll and Wake Island, are under the jurisdiction of the US Federal Government Department of the Interior, as part of the Pacific Islands Heritage Marine National Monument.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] As such, all US Federal laws regarding age of consent would be applicable.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/age-of-consent-in-the-united-states-p04] Midway Atoll is under the jurisdiction of the US Federal Government Department of the Interior (administered as a National Wildlife Refuge).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/agriculture-commissioner] In the state governments of the United States, all 50 states have the executive position of **agriculture commissioner**, **director of agriculture**, or **secretary of agriculture**.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/agriculture-commissioner] This official is in charge of the state's agriculture department.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/agriculture-commissioner] The agriculture commissioners are organized at the national level by the National Association of State Departments of Agriculture.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/agriculture-commissioner] The agriculture commissioner is elected in 12 states: Alabama, Florida, Georgia, Iowa, Kentucky, Louisiana, Mississippi, North Carolina, North Dakota, South Carolina, Texas, and West Virginia.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/agriculture-commissioner] The powers and duties of the office vary from state to state, but are often substantial: in about 40 states, agriculture departments regulate the animal industry, and in roughly half the states, agriculture departments regulate food safety and meat inspection.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/agriculture-commissioner] In some states, the agriculture commissioner has more power.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/agriculture-commissioner] For example, in Florida the agriculture commissioner is one of four members of the Florida Cabinet (along with the governor, chief financial officer, and attorney general), giving the commissioner some influence over state policy beyond agriculture.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/agriculture-commissioner] In North Dakota, the agriculture commissioner sits on a number of important boards, such as the North Dakota Industrial Commission (which oversees the state-owned North Dakota Mill and Elevator and Bank of North Dakota).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] The **Alabama Department of Agriculture and Industries (ADAI)** is an independent agency of the government of Alabama first created by an Act of the State Legislature on February 23, 1883.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] The Department is responsible for serving farmers and consumers of agricultural products and operates with an annual budget of just under $25 million.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] The Department has about 300 full-time employees and 250 part-time employees.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] The Department is under the direction and supervision of the Commissioner of Agriculture and Industries.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] Betts of Madison County and he was appointed by then Governor of Alabama, Edward A.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] In 1891, the legislature changed it to a statewide elected office chosen in partisan elections, but allowing the Governor to fill vacancies that occur during a term due to death or resignation.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] Commissioners have always been eligible to serve an unlimited number of terms, but not consecutively.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] Beginning with the 1970 election Commissioners were then allowed to serve two consecutive terms.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] The current and 30th Commissioner is Rick Pate of Lowndes County who was elected in November, 2018 and assumed office on January 14, 2019.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] His immediate predecessor and the 29th Commissioner was John McMillan, a Republican first elected in November 2010 and not eligible to seek a third consecutive term.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] Commissioner McMillan previously worked for the Alabama Forestry Commission.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] Jack Thompson was the first Republican elected Commissioner.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] Both Commissioners Pete Gilmer and McMillan Lane were first appointed to office by Governor George C.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] Wallace upon the death of their predecessors.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] Todd not only has the distinction of being the only Commissioner to serve three terms, but he was both the youngest and the oldest Commissioner.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-commissioner-of-agriculture] The Commissioner is assisted in managing the Department by a Deputy Commissioner and Chief of Staff, two Deputy Commissioners and one Assistant Commissioner.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama is nicknamed the *Yellowhammer State*, after the state bird.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama is also known as the "Heart of Dixie" and the "Cotton State".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The state has diverse geography, with the north dominated by the mountainous Tennessee Valley and the south by Mobile Bay.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama's capital is Montgomery, and its largest city by population and area is Huntsville.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Its oldest city is Mobile, founded by French colonists (Alabama Creoles) in 1702 as the capital of French Louisiana.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Greater Birmingham is Alabama's largest metropolitan area and its economic center.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Politically, as part of the Deep South, or "Bible Belt", Alabama is a predominantly conservative state and is known for its Southern culture.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Within Alabama, American football, particularly at the college level, is part of the state's culture.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Originally the area of Alabama was home to many native tribes.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] It was a Spanish territory from the sixteenth century until the French acquired it in the early eighteenth century.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The British won the territory in 1763 until losing it in the American Revolutionary War.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Spain held Mobile as part of Spanish West Florida until 1813.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In December 1819, Alabama was recognized as a state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] During the antebellum period, Alabama was a major producer of cotton and widely used African American slave labor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In 1861, the state seceded from the United States to become part of the Confederate States of America, with Montgomery acting as its first capital.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Following the American Civil War, it would suffer decades of economic hardship, in part due to agriculture and a few cash crops being the main driver of the state's economy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Similar to other former slave states, Alabamian legislators employed Jim Crow laws from the late 19th century until the 1960s.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] High-profile events such as the Selma to Montgomery marches made the state a focal point of the civil rights movement in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] During and after World War II, the state's economy diversified with new industries.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In 1960, the establishment of NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville helped boost Alabama's economic growth by developing a local aerospace industry.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama's economy in the 21st century is based on automotive, finance, tourism, manufacturing, aerospace, mineral extraction, healthcare, education, retail, and technology.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Despite the economic and industrial growth in recent decades, Alabama typically ranks low in terms of health outcomes, educational attainment, and median household income.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The name of the Alabama River and state is derived from the Alabama people, a Muskogean-speaking tribe whose members lived just below the confluence of the Coosa and Tallapoosa rivers on the upper reaches of the river.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In the Alabama language, the word for a person of Alabama lineage is *Albaamo* (or variously *Albaama* or *Albàamo* in different dialects; the plural form is *Albaamaha*).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The word's spelling varies significantly among historical sources.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The first usage appears in three accounts of the Hernando de Soto expedition of 1540: Garcilaso de la Vega used *Alibamo*, while the Knight of Elvas and Rodrigo Ranjel wrote *Alibamu* and *Limamu*, respectively, in transliterations of the term.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] As early as 1702, the French called the tribe the *Alibamon*, with French maps identifying the river as *Rivière des Alibamons*.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Other spellings of the name have included *Alibamu*, *Alabamo*, *Albama*, *Alebamon*, *Alibama*, *Alibamou*, *Alabamu*, and *Allibamou*.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The use of state names derived from Native American languages is common in the U.S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] An estimated 26 states have names of Native American origin.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Some scholars suggest the word comes from the Choctaw *alba* (meaning 'plants' or 'weeds') and *amo* (meaning 'to cut', 'to trim', or 'to gather').
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The meaning may have been 'clearers of the thicket' or 'herb gatherers', referring to clearing land for cultivation or collecting medicinal plants.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The state has numerous place names of Native American origin.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] An 1842 article in the *Jacksonville Republican* proposed it meant 'Here We Rest'.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] This notion was popularized in the 1850s through the writings of Alexander Beaufort Meek.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Experts in the Muskogean languages have not found any evidence to support such a translation.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Indigenous peoples of varying cultures lived in the area for thousands of years before the advent of European colonization.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Trade with the northeastern tribes by the Ohio River began during the Burial Mound Period (1000 BC – 700 AD) and continued until European contact.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The agrarian Mississippian culture covered most of the state from 1000 to 1600 AD, with one of its major polities centered around what is now the Moundville Archaeological Site in Moundville, Alabama.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] This is the second-largest complex of the classic Middle Mississippian era, after Cahokia in present-day Illinois, which was the earliest center of the culture.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Analysis of artifacts from archaeological excavations at Moundville were the basis of scholars' formulating the characteristics of the Southeastern Ceremonial Complex (SECC).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Contrary to popular belief, the SECC appears to have no direct links to Mesoamerican culture but developed independently.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The Ceremonial Complex represents a major component of the religion of the Mississippian peoples; it is one of the primary means by which their religion is understood.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Among the historical tribes of Native American people living in present-day Alabama at the time of European contact were the Cherokee, an Iroquoian language people; and the Muskogean-speaking Alabama (*Alibamu*), Chickasaw, Choctaw, Creek, and Koasati.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] While part of the same large language family, the Muskogee tribes developed distinct cultures and languages.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The Spanish were the first Europeans to reach Alabama during their exploration of North America in the 16th century.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The expedition of Hernando de Soto passed through Mabila and other parts of the state in 1540.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] More than 160 years later, the French founded the region's first European settlement at Old Mobile in 1702.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The city was moved to the current site of Mobile in 1711.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] This area was claimed by the French from 1702 to 1763 as part of La Louisiane.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] After the French lost to the British in the Seven Years' War, it became part of British West Florida from 1763 to 1783.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] After the U.S. victory in the American Revolutionary War, the territory was divided between the United States and Spain.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The latter retained control of this western territory from 1783 until the surrender of the Spanish garrison at Mobile to U.S. forces on April 13, 1813.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Thomas Bassett, a loyalist to the British monarchy during the Revolutionary era, was one of the earliest white settlers in the state outside Mobile.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] He settled in the Tombigbee District during the early 1770s.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The district's boundaries were roughly limited to the area within a few miles of the Tombigbee River and included portions of what is today southern Clarke County, northernmost Mobile County, and most of Washington County.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] What are now Baldwin and Mobile counties became part of Spanish West Florida in 1783, part of the independent Republic of West Florida in 1810, and finally part of the Mississippi Territory in 1812.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Most of what is now the northern two-thirds of Alabama was known as the Yazoo lands beginning during the British colonial period.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] It was claimed by the Province of Georgia from 1767 onwards.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Following the American Revolutionary War, it remained a part of Georgia, although heavily disputed.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] With the exception of the area around Mobile and the Yazoo lands, what is now the lower one-third of Alabama was made part of the Mississippi Territory when it was organized in 1798.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The Yazoo lands were added to the territory in 1804, following the Yazoo land scandal.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Spain kept a claim on its former Spanish West Florida territory in what would become the coastal counties until the Adams–Onís Treaty officially ceded it to the U.S. in 1819.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The creation of the Mississippi Territory quickly prompted debates over its division.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Amid pressure from white southerners who sought the establishment of two slave states, Congress formed the Alabama Territory from the eastern half of the Mississippi Territory on March 3, 1817.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The legislation appointed William Wyatt Bibb of Georgia as the first governor of the newly designated Alabama Territory.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Before Mississippi's admission to statehood on December 10, 1817, the more sparsely settled eastern half of the territory was separated and named the Alabama Territory.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The United States Congress created the Alabama Territory on March 3, 1817.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Stephens, now abandoned, served as the territorial capital from 1817 to 1819.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama was admitted as the 22nd state on December 14, 1819, with Congress selecting Huntsville as the site for the first Constitutional Convention.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] From July 5 to August 2, 1819, delegates met to prepare the new state constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Huntsville served as temporary capital from 1819 to 1820, when the seat of government moved to Cahaba in Dallas County.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Cahaba, now a ghost town, was the first permanent state capital from 1820 to 1825.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The Alabama Fever land rush was underway when the state was admitted to the Union, with settlers and land speculators pouring into the state to take advantage of fertile land suitable for cotton cultivation.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Part of the frontier in the 1820s and 1830s, its constitution provided for universal suffrage for white men.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Southeastern planters and traders from the Upper South brought slaves with them as the cotton plantations in Alabama expanded.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The economy of the central Black Belt (named for its dark, productive soil) was built around large cotton plantations whose owners' wealth grew mainly from slave labor.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The area also drew many poor, disenfranchised people who became subsistence farmers.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama had an estimated population of under 10,000 people in 1810, but it increased to more than 300,000 people by 1830.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Most Native American tribes were completely removed from the state within a few years of the passage of the Indian Removal Act by Congress in 1830.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] From 1826 to 1846, Tuscaloosa served as Alabama's capital.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] On January 30, 1846, the Alabama legislature announced it had voted to move the capital city from Tuscaloosa to Montgomery.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The first legislative session in the new capital met in December 1847.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] A new capitol building was erected under the direction of Stephen Decatur Button of Philadelphia.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The first structure burned down in 1849, but was rebuilt on the same site in 1851.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] This second capitol building in Montgomery remains to the present day.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] It was designed by Barachias Holt of Exeter, Maine.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] By 1860, the population had increased to 964,201 people, of which nearly half, 435,080, were enslaved African Americans, and 2,690 were free people of color.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] On January 11, 1861, Alabama declared its secession from the Union.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] After remaining an independent republic for a few days, it joined the Confederate States of America.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The Confederacy's capital was initially at Montgomery.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama was heavily involved in the American Civil War.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Although comparatively few battles were fought in the state, Alabama contributed about 120,000 soldiers to the war effort.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] A company of cavalry soldiers from Huntsville, Alabama, joined Nathan Bedford Forrest's battalion in Hopkinsville, Kentucky.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The company wore new uniforms with yellow trim on the sleeves, collar and coattails.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] This led to them being greeted with "Yellowhammer", and the name later was applied to all Alabama troops in the Confederate Army.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama's slaves were freed by the 13th Amendment in 1865.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama was under military rule from the end of the war in May 1865 until its official restoration to the Union in 1868.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] From 1867 to 1874, with most white citizens barred temporarily from voting and freedmen enfranchised, many African Americans emerged as political leaders in the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama was represented in Congress during this period by three African-American congressmen: Jeremiah Haralson, Benjamin S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Following the war, the state remained chiefly agricultural, with an economy tied to cotton.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] During the Reconstruction era, state legislators ratified a new state constitution in 1868 which created the state's first public school system and expanded women's rights.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Legislators funded numerous public road and railroad projects, although these were plagued with allegations of fraud and misappropriation.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Organized insurgent, resistance groups tried to suppress the freedmen and Republicans.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] These groups included The Ku Klux Klan, the Pale Faces, Knights of the White Camellia, Red Shirts, and the White League.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Reconstruction in Alabama ended in 1874, when the Democrats regained control of the legislature and governor's office through an election dominated by fraud and violence.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] They wrote another constitution in 1875, and the legislature passed the Blaine Amendment, prohibiting public money from being used to finance religiously affiliated schools.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The same year, legislation was approved that called for racially segregated schools.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Railroad passenger cars were segregated in 1891.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The 1901 constitution required racial segregation of public schools.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] By 1903 only 2,980 African Americans were registered in Alabama, although at least 74,000 were literate.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] This compared to more than 181,000 African Americans eligible to vote in 1900.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The numbers dropped even more in later decades.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The state legislature passed additional racial segregation laws related to public facilities into the 1950s: jails were segregated in 1911; hospitals in 1915; toilets, hotels, and restaurants in 1928; and bus stop waiting rooms in 1945.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] While the planter class had persuaded poor whites to vote for this legislative effort to suppress black voting, the new restrictions resulted in their disenfranchisement as well, due mostly to the imposition of a cumulative poll tax.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] By 1941, whites constituted a slight majority of those disenfranchised by these laws: 600,000 whites vs.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Nearly all blacks had lost the ability to vote.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Despite numerous legal challenges which succeeded in overturning certain provisions, the state legislature would create new ones to maintain disenfranchisement.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The exclusion of blacks from the political system persisted until after passage of federal civil rights legislation in 1965 to enforce their constitutional rights as citizens.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The rural-dominated Alabama legislature consistently underfunded schools and services for the disenfranchised African Americans, but it did not relieve them of paying taxes.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Partially as a response to chronic underfunding of education for African Americans in the South, the Rosenwald Fund began funding the construction of what came to be known as Rosenwald Schools.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In Alabama, these schools were designed, and the construction partially financed with Rosenwald funds, which paid one-third of the construction costs.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The fund required the local community and state to raise matching funds to pay the rest.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Black residents effectively taxed themselves twice, by raising additional monies to supply matching funds for such schools, which were built in many rural areas.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] They often donated land and labor as well.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Beginning in 1913, the first 80 Rosenwald Schools were built in Alabama for African American children.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] A total of 387 schools, seven teachers' houses, and several vocational buildings were completed by 1937 in the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Several of the surviving school buildings in the state are now listed on the National Register of Historic Places.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Reflecting this emigration, the population growth rate in Alabama (see "historical populations" table below) dropped by nearly half from 1910 to 1920.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] At the same time, many rural people migrated to the city of Birmingham to work in new industrial jobs.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Birmingham experienced such rapid growth it was called the "Magic City".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] By 1920, Birmingham was the 36th-largest city in the United States.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Heavy industry and mining were the basis of its economy.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Its residents were under-represented for decades in the state legislature, which refused to redistrict after each decennial census according to population changes, as it was required by the state constitution.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] This did not change until the late 1960s following a lawsuit and court order.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Industrial development related to the demands of World War II brought a level of prosperity to the state not seen since before the civil war.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Rural workers poured into the largest cities in the state for better jobs and a higher standard of living.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] One example of this massive influx of workers occurred in Mobile.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Between 1940 and 1943, more than 89,000 people moved into the city to work for war-related industries.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Cotton and other cash crops faded in importance as the state developed a manufacturing and service base.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Despite massive population changes in the state from 1901 to 1961, the rural-dominated legislature refused to reapportion House and Senate seats based on population, as required by the state constitution to follow the results of decennial censuses.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] They held on to old representation to maintain political and economic power in agricultural areas.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] One result was that Jefferson County, containing Birmingham's industrial and economic powerhouse, contributed more than one-third of all tax revenue to the state, but did not receive a proportional amount in services.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Urban interests were consistently underrepresented in the legislature.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In the United States Supreme Court cases of *Baker v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Sims* (1964), the court ruled that the principle of "one man, one vote" needed to be the basis of both houses of state legislatures, and that their districts had to be based on population rather than geographic counties.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] African Americans continued to press in the 1950s and 1960s to end disenfranchisement and segregation in the state through the civil rights movement, including legal challenges.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Board of Education* that public schools had to be desegregated, but Alabama was slow to comply.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] During the 1960s, under Governor George Wallace, Alabama resisted compliance with federal demands for desegregation.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The civil rights movement had notable events in Alabama, including the Montgomery bus boycott (1955–1956), Freedom Rides in 1961, and 1965 Selma to Montgomery marches.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] These contributed to Congressional passage and enactment of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and Voting Rights Act of 1965 by the U.S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Legal segregation ended in the states in 1964, although Jim Crow customs often continued until specifically challenged in court.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] According to *The New York Times*, by 2017, many of Alabama's African Americans were living in Alabama's cities such as Birmingham and Montgomery.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Also, the Black Belt region across central Alabama "is home to largely poor counties that are predominantly African-American.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In 1972, for the first time since 1901, the legislature completed the congressional redistricting based on the decennial census.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] This benefited the urban areas that had developed, as well as all in the population who had been underrepresented for more than sixty years.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Other changes were made to implement representative state house and senate districts.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama has made some changes since the late 20th century and has used new types of voting to increase representation.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In the 1980s, an omnibus redistricting case, *Dillard v.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Crenshaw County*, challenged the at-large voting for representative seats of 180 Alabama jurisdictions, including counties and school boards.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] At-large voting had diluted the votes of any minority in a county, as the majority tended to take all seats.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Despite African Americans making up a significant minority in the state, they had been unable to elect any representatives in most of the at-large jurisdictions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] As part of settlement of this case, five Alabama cities and counties, including Chilton County, adopted a system of cumulative voting for election of representatives in multi-seat jurisdictions.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] This has resulted in more proportional representation for voters.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In another form of proportional representation, 23 jurisdictions use limited voting, as in Conecuh County.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In 1982, limited voting was first tested in Conecuh County.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Together use of these systems has increased the number of African Americans and women being elected to local offices, resulting in governments that are more representative of their citizens.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Beginning in the 1960s, the state's economy shifted away from its traditional lumber, steel, and textile industries because of increased foreign competition.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] However, the state, particularly Huntsville, benefited from the opening of the George C.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Marshall Space Flight Center in 1960, a major facility in the development of the Saturn rocket program and the space shuttle.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Technology and manufacturing industries, such as automobile assembly, replaced some of the state's older industries in the late twentieth century, but the state's economy and growth lagged behind other states in the area, such as Georgia and Florida.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In 2001, Alabama Supreme Court chief justice Roy Moore installed a statue of the Ten Commandments in the capitol in Montgomery.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Circuit Court ordered the statue removed, but Moore refused to follow the court order, which led to protests around the capitol in favor of keeping the monument.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The monument was removed in August 2003.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] A few natural disasters have occurred in the state in the twenty-first century.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In 2004, Hurricane Ivan, a category 3 storm upon landfall, struck the state and caused over $18 billion of damage.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] It was among the most destructive storms to strike the state in its modern history.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] A super outbreak of 62 tornadoes hit the state in April 2011 and killed 238 people, devastating many communities.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama is the thirtieth-largest state in the United States with 52,419 square miles (135,760 km2) of total area: 3.2% of the area is water, making Alabama 23rd in the amount of surface water, also giving it the second-largest inland waterway system in the United States.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] About three-fifths of the land area is part of the Gulf Coastal Plain, a gentle plain with a general descent towards the Mississippi River and the Gulf of Mexico.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The North Alabama region is mostly mountainous, with the Tennessee River cutting a large valley and creating numerous creeks, streams, rivers, mountains, and lakes.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama is bordered by the states of Tennessee to the north, Georgia to the east, Florida to the south, and Mississippi to the west.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama has a coastline on the Gulf of Mexico, in the extreme southern edge of the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The state ranges in elevation from sea level at Mobile Bay to more than 2,000 feet (610 m) in the northeast, to Mount Cheaha at 2,413 ft (735 m).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama's land consists of 22 million acres (89,000 km2) of forest or 67% of the state's total land area.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Suburban Baldwin County, along the Gulf Coast, is the largest county in the state in both land area and water area.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Additionally, Alabama has four National Forests: Conecuh, Talladega, Tuskegee, and William B.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama also contains the Natchez Trace Parkway, the Selma To Montgomery National Historic Trail, and the Trail of Tears National Historic Trail.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] A 5-mile (8 km)-wide meteorite impact crater is located in Elmore County, just north of Montgomery.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] This is the Wetumpka crater, the site of "Alabama's greatest natural disaster".
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] A 1,000-foot (300 m)-wide meteorite hit the area about 80 million years ago.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In 2002, Christian Koeberl with the Institute of Geochemistry University of Vienna published evidence and established the site as the 157th recognized impact crater on Earth.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The state is classified as humid subtropical (*Cfa*) under the Köppen climate classification.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The average annual temperature is 64 °F (18 °C).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Temperatures tend to be warmer in the southern part of the state with its proximity to the Gulf of Mexico, while the northern parts of the state, especially in the Appalachian Mountains in the northeast, tend to be slightly cooler.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Generally, Alabama has very hot summers and mild winters with copious precipitation throughout the year.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama receives an average of 56 inches (1,400 mm) of rainfall annually and enjoys a lengthy growing season of up to 300 days in the southern part of the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Summers in Alabama are among the hottest in the U.S., with high temperatures averaging over 90 °F (32 °C) throughout the summer in some parts of the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama is also prone to tropical storms and hurricanes.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Areas of the state far away from the Gulf are not immune to the effects of the storms, which often dump tremendous amounts of rain as they move inland and weaken.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] South Alabama reports many thunderstorms.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The Gulf Coast, around Mobile Bay, averages between 70 and 80 days per year with thunder reported.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] This activity decreases somewhat further north in the state, but even the far north of the state reports thunder on about 60 days per year.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Occasionally, thunderstorms are severe with frequent lightning and large hail; the central and northern parts of the state are most vulnerable to this type of storm.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama ranks ninth in the number of deaths from lightning and tenth in the number of deaths from lightning strikes per capita.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama, along with Oklahoma and Iowa, has the most confirmed F5 and EF5 tornadoes of any state, according to statistics from the National Climatic Data Center for the period January 1, 1950, to June 2013.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Several long-tracked F5/EF5 tornadoes have contributed to Alabama reporting more tornado fatalities since 1950 than any other state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The state was affected by the 1974 Super Outbreak and was devastated tremendously by the 2011 Super Outbreak.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The 2011 Super Outbreak produced a record amount of tornadoes in the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The peak season for tornadoes varies from the northern to southern parts of the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama is one of the few places in the world that has a secondary tornado season in November and December besides the typically severe spring.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The northern part—along the Tennessee River Valley—is most vulnerable.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The area of Alabama and Mississippi most affected by tornadoes is sometimes referred to as Dixie Alley, as distinct from the Tornado Alley of the Southern Plains.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Winters are generally mild in Alabama, as they are throughout most of the Southeastern United States, with average January low temperatures around 40 °F (4 °C) in Mobile and around 32 °F (0 °C) in Birmingham.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Although snow is a rare event in much of Alabama, areas of the state north of Montgomery may receive a dusting of snow a few times every winter, with an occasional moderately heavy snowfall every few years.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Historic snowfall events include New Year's Eve 1963 snowstorm and the 1993 Storm of the Century.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The annual average snowfall for the Birmingham area is 2 inches (51 mm) per year.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In the southern Gulf coast, snowfall is less frequent, sometimes going several years without any snowfall.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama's highest temperature of 112 °F (44 °C) was recorded on September 5, 1925, in the unincorporated community of Centerville.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The record low of −27 °F (−33 °C) occurred on January 30, 1966, in New Market.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The state is usually ranked among the top in nation for its range of overall biodiversity.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama is in the subtropical coniferous forest biome and once boasted huge expanses of pine forest, which still form the largest proportion of forests in the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] It currently ranks fifth in the nation for the diversity of its flora.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] It is home to nearly 4,000 pteridophyte and spermatophyte plant species.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Indigenous animal species in the state include 62 mammal species, 93 reptile species, 73 amphibian species, roughly 307 native freshwater fish species, and 420 bird species that spend at least part of their year within the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Invertebrates include 97 crayfish species and 383 mollusk species.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] 113 of these mollusk species have never been collected outside the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] As of 2010, the state contains 461 municipalities, consisting of 174 cities and 287 towns.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Covering only 9.6% of Alabama's land mass, its municipalities are home to 60.4% of its population.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Montgomery, the state's capital, is the third-most populous settlement in Alabama; and the most populous city is Huntsville.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Census Bureau, the state contains 12 metropolitan statistical areas.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama's largest metropolitan area was Greater Birmingham.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] At the 1800 United States census, Alabama had a population of 1,250 people.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Since then, the state has continued to experience population growth with every U.S. census.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] According to the 2020 United States census the population of Alabama was 5,024,279, which represents an increase of 244,543 or 5.12%, since the 2010 census.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] This includes a natural increase since the last census of 121,054 (502,457 births minus 381,403 deaths) and an increase due to net migration of 104,991 into the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] According to statistics from 2012, immigration from outside the U.S. resulted in a net increase of 31,180 people, and migration within the country produced a net gain of 73,811 people.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The state had 108,000 foreign-born residents (2.4% of the state population), of which an estimated 22.2% were undocumented (24,000).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The top countries of origin for immigrants were Mexico, China, India, Germany and Guatemala as of 2018.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] According to HUD's 2022 Annual Homeless Assessment Report, there were an estimated 3,752 homeless people in Alabama.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] With a population density of 99.2 people per square mile as of 2020, the majority of the state's population lives in North, Central, and South Alabama, spread throughout the Huntsville, Birmingham, Montgomery and Mobile metropolitan statistical areas.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The center of population of Alabama is located in Chilton County, outside the town of Jemison.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Many American Indian tribes such as the Cherokee, Chickasaw, Choctaw, and Coushatta inhabited present-day Alabama before European colonization.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] With Spanish, French, and British colonization of Alabama, white and black Americans migrated to the area.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] From European colonization to U.S. statehood, Alabama's population grew to become increasingly non-Hispanic white and African American.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] By the 2020 census, Alabama's total racial and ethnic population was 66.5% non-Hispanic white and 26.9% African American, with a growing Hispanic and Latino population of 5.3%.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabamians citing "American" ancestry are of overwhelmingly English extraction.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Demographers estimate that a minimum of 20–23% of people in Alabama are of predominantly English ancestry and state that the figure is probably much higher.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In the 1980 census, 1,139,976 people in Alabama cited that they were of English ancestry out of a total state population of 2,824,719 making them 41% of the state at the time and the largest ethnic group.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama has the 5th-highest black and African American population among U.S. states at 25.8% alone as of 2020.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In 2011, 46.6% of Alabama's population younger than age 1 were minorities.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The Scots-Irish were the largest non-English immigrant group from the British Isles before the American Revolution, and many settled in the South, later moving into the Deep South as it was developed.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In 1984, under the Davis–Strong Act, the state legislature established the Alabama Indian Affairs Commission.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Indigenous groups within the state had increasingly been demanding recognition as ethnic groups and seeking an end to discrimination.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Given the long history of slavery and associated racial segregation, the Native American or American Indian peoples, who have sometimes been of mixed race, have insisted on having their cultural identification respected.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In the past, their self-identification was often overlooked as the state tried to impose a binary breakdown of society into white and black.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The state has officially recognized nine American Indian tribes in the state, descended mostly from the Five Civilized Tribes of the American Southeast.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The state government has promoted recognition of American Indian contributions to the state, including the designation in 2000 for Columbus Day to be jointly celebrated as American Indian Heritage Day.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In 2020, 33,625 identified as being Native American alone, and 97,405 did in combination with one or more other races.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] According to the 2022 American Community Survey's estimates, approximately 94% of Alabamians speak English as their sole language, while 6% spoke a language other than English.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Of other languages, the majority of its multilingual population speaks Spanish (3.8%).
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In a separate 2021 study by the American University Washington College of Law, Spanish was spoken by 156,656 residents.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Following, Korean, Vietnamese, Mandarin and Cantonese, German, French, and Tagalog were the most-spoken languages; among its French-speaking population, the majority have preserved their language since French colonization.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Pre-colonial and present-day Alabamians have adhered to multiple religions including Native American and African diaspora religions, and predominantly Christianity with the establishment of Spanish missions in Florida.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Other faiths including Judaism, Islam, and Indian religions were introduced since European colonization and American settlement.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] According to a 2023 Public Religion Research Institute survey, an estimated 80% of the adult population were Christian.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In the 2008 American Religious Identification Survey, 86% of Alabama respondents reported their religion as Christian, including 6% Catholic, with 11% as having no religion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The composition of other traditions is 0.5% Mormon, 0.5% Jewish, 0.5% Muslim, 0.5% Buddhist, and 0.5% Hindu.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama is located in the middle of the Bible Belt, a region of numerous Protestant Christians.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama has been identified as one of the most religious states in the United States, with about 58% of the population attending church regularly.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] A majority of people in the state identify as Evangelical Protestant.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] As of 2010, the three largest denominational groups in Alabama are the Southern Baptist Convention, The United Methodist Church, and non-denominational Evangelical Protestant.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In Alabama, the Southern Baptist Convention has the highest number of adherents with 1,380,121; this is followed by the United Methodist Church with 327,734 adherents, non-denominational Evangelical Protestant with 220,938 adherents, and the Catholic Church with 150,647 adherents.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Many Baptist and Methodist congregations became established in the Great Awakening of the early 19th century, when preachers proselytized across the South.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The Assemblies of God had almost 60,000 members, the Churches of Christ had nearly 120,000 members.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In a 2007 survey, nearly 70% of respondents could name all four of the Christian Gospels.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Of those who indicated a religious preference, 59% said they possessed a "full understanding" of their faith and needed no further learning.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In a 2007 poll, 92% of Alabamians reported having at least some confidence in churches in the state.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Although in much smaller numbers, many other religious faiths are represented in the state as well, including Judaism, Islam, Hinduism, Buddhism, Sikhism, the Baháʼí Faith, and Unitarian Universalism.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Jews have been present in what is now Alabama since 1763, during the colonial era of Mobile, when Sephardic Jews immigrated from London.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The oldest Jewish congregation in the state is Congregation Sha'arai Shomayim in Mobile.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] It was formally recognized by the state legislature on January 25, 1844.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Later immigrants in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries tended to be Ashkenazi Jews from eastern Europe.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Jewish denominations in the state include two Orthodox, four Conservative, ten Reform, and one Humanistic synagogue.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Muslims have been increasing in Alabama, with 31 mosques built by 2011, many by African-American converts.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] There are six Dharma centers and organizations for Theravada Buddhists.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Most monastic Buddhist temples are concentrated in southern Mobile County, near Bayou La Batre.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] This area has attracted an influx of refugees from Cambodia, Laos, and Vietnam during the 1970s and thereafter.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The four temples within a ten-mile radius of Bayou La Batre, include Chua Chanh Giac, Wat Buddharaksa, and Wat Lao Phoutthavihan.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] The first community of adherents of the Baháʼí Faith in Alabama was founded in 1896 by Paul K.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Dealy, who moved from Chicago to Fairhope.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Baháʼí centers in Alabama exist in Birmingham, Huntsville, and Florence.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] In 2018, life expectancy in Alabama was 75.1 years, below the national average of 78.7 years and is the third lowest life expectancy in the country.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Factors that can cause lower life expectancy are maternal mortality, suicide, and gun crimes.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] A Centers for Disease Control and Prevention study in 2008 showed that obesity in Alabama is a problem, with most counties having more than 29% of adults obese, except for ten which had a rate between 26% and 29%.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Residents of the state, along with those in five other states, were least likely in the nation to be physically active during leisure time.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p01] Alabama, and the southeastern U.S. in general, has one of the highest incidences of adult onset diabetes in the country, exceeding 10% of adults.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] Bureau of Economic Analysis, in 2025, Alabama's total gross state product was $341.1 billion, and the state's per capita personal income was $59,677.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] The state has invested in aerospace, education, health care, banking, and various heavy industries, including automobile manufacturing, mineral extraction, steel production and fabrication.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] By 2006, crop and animal production in Alabama was valued at $1.5 billion.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] In contrast to the primarily agricultural economy of the previous century, this was only about one percent of the state's gross domestic product.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] The number of private farms has declined at a steady rate since the 1960s, as land has been sold to developers, timber companies, and large farming conglomerates.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] In 2025, 99.4% of Alabama businesses were small businesses and employed 46.0% of the state's workforce.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] The state's seasonally adjusted unemployment rate was 5.8% in April 2015.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] This compared to a nationwide seasonally adjusted rate of 5.4%.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] As of May 2025, the unemployment rate was 3.3%.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] Alabama has no minimum wage and in February 2016 passed legislation preventing municipalities from setting one.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] As of 2018, Alabama has the sixth highest poverty rate among states in the U.S.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] In 2017, United Nations Special Rapporteur Philip Alston toured parts of rural Alabama and observed environmental conditions that he said were poorer than anywhere he had seen in the developed world.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] Alabama's agricultural outputs include poultry and eggs, cattle, fish, plant nursery items, peanuts, cotton, grains such as corn and sorghum, vegetables, milk, soybeans, and peaches.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] Although known as "The Cotton State", Alabama ranks between eighth and tenth in national cotton production, according to various reports, with Texas, Georgia and Mississippi comprising the top three.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] Aquaculture is a large part of the economy of Alabama.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] Alabamians began to practice aquaculture in the early 1960s.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] U.S. farm-raised catfish is the 8th most popular seafood product in America.
[src:agriculture-commissioner/alabama-p02] By 2008, approximately 4,000 people in Alabama were employed by the catfish industry and Alabama produced 132 million pounds of catfish.
